nrolment almost always occurred within the first 24 hours after birth.\n> 13 Adapted and integrated from the 2013 _WHO recommendations on postnatal care of the mother and newborn_ .\n> 14 Adapted and/or integrated from the 2020 _Improving early childhood development: WHO guideline_ .\nExecutive summary\n**xiii**\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nCare category Recommendation Category of<br>recommendation<br>Breastfeeding<br>Exclusive  42.  All babies should be exclusively breastfed from birth until 6 months  Recommended<br>breastfeeding [15] of age. Mothers should be counselled and provided with support for<br>exclusive breastfeeding at each postnatal contact.<br>Protecting, promoting  43a.  Facilities providing maternity and newborn services should have a  Recommended<br>and supporting  clearly written breastfeeding policy that is routinely communicated to<br>breastfeeding in  staff and parents.<br>facilities providing<br>maternity and  43b.  Health-facility staff who provide infant feeding services, including  Recommended<br>newborn services [16] breastfeeding support, should have sufficient knowledge, competence<br>and skills to support women to breastfeed.<br>C. HEALTH SYSTEMS AND HEALTH PROMOTION INTERVENTIONS<br>Schedules for  44.  A minimum of four postnatal care contacts is recommended. Recommended<br>postnatal care<br>If birth is in a health facility, healthy women and newborns should<br>contacts<br>receive postnatal care in the facility for at least 24 hours after birth.<br>If birth is at home, the first postnatal contact should be as early as<br>possible within 24 hours of birth. At least three additional postnatal<br>contacts are recommended for healthy women and newborns, between<br>48 and 72 hours, between 7 and 14 days, and during week six after<br>birth.<br>Length of stay in  45.  Care for healthy women and newborns in the health facility is  Recommended<br>health facilities after  recommended for at least 24 hours after vaginal birth.<br>birth<br>Criteria to be  46.  Prior to discharging women and newborns after birth from the  Recommended<br>assessed prior to  health facility to the home, health workers should assess the following<br>discharge from the  criteria to improve maternal and newborn outcomes:<br>health facility after  • the woman’s and baby’s physical well-being and the woman’s<br>birth emotional well-being;<br>• the skills and confidence of the woman to care for herself and the<br>skills and confidence of the parents and caregivers to care for the<br>newborn; and<br>• the home environment and other factors that may influence the<br>ability to provide care for the woman and the newborn in the<br>home, and care-seeking behaviour.<br>Approaches  47.  Information provision, educational interventions and counselling  Recommended<br>to strengthen  are recommended to prepare women, parents and caregivers for<br>preparation for  discharge from the health facility after birth to improve maternal and<br>discharge from the  newborn health outcomes, and to facilitate the transition to the home.<br>health facility to  Educational materials, such as written/digital education booklets,<br>home after birth pictorials for semi-literate populations and job aids should be available.<br>Home visits for  48.  Home visits during the first week after birth by skilled health  Recommended<br>postnatal care  personnel or a trained community health worker are recommended for<br>contacts  the postnatal care of healthy women and newborns. Where home visits<br>are not feasible or not preferred, outpatient postnatal care contacts are<br>recommended.<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n> 15 Integrated from the 2014 _WHO recommendations on postnatal care of the mother and newborn_ .\n> 16 Integrated from the 2017 WHO guideline _Protecting, promoting and supporting breastfeeding in facilities providing maternity and newborn services_ .\n**xiv**\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nCare category Recommendation Category of<br>recommendation<br>Midwifery continuity  49.  Midwife-led continuity-of-care (MLCC) models, in which a  Context-specific<br>of care [17] known midwife or small group of known midwives supports a woman  recommendation<br>throughout the antenatal, intrapartum and postnatal continuum, are<br>recommended for women in settings with well-functioning midwifery<br>programmes.<br>Task sharing  50a.  Task sharing the promotion of health-related behaviours for  Recommended<br>components of  maternal and newborn health [g]  to a broad range of cadres, including<br>postnatal care  lay health workers, auxiliary nurses, nurses, midwives and doctors, is<br>delivery [18] recommended.<br>50b.  Task sharing the provision of recommended postpartum  Recommended<br>contraception methods [h]  to a broad range of cadres, including auxiliary<br>nurses, nurses, midwives and doctors, is recommended.<br>Recruitment and  51.  Policy-makers should consider a bundle of interventions covering  Recommended<br>retention of staff  education, regulation, incentives and personal and professional support<br>in rural and remote  to improve health workforce development, attraction, recruitment and<br>areas [19] retention in rural and remote areas.<br>Involvement of men  52.  Interventions to promote the involvement of men during pregnancy,  Recommended with<br>in postnatal care  childbirth and after birth are recommended to facilitate and support  targeted monitoring<br>and maternal and  improved self-care of women, home care practices for women and  and evaluation<br>newborn health [20] newborns, and use of skilled care for women and newborns during<br>pregnancy, childbirth and the postnatal period, and to increase the<br>timely use of facility care for obstetric and newborn complications.<br>These interventions are recommended, provided they are implemented<br>in a way that respects, promotes and facilitates women’s choices and<br>their autonomy in decision-making, and that supports women in taking<br>care of themselves and their newborns.<br>Home-based records [21] 53.  The use of home-based records, as a complement to facility-based  Recommended<br>records, is recommended for the care of pregnant and postpartum<br>women, newborns and children, to improve care-seeking behaviour,<br>men’s involvement and support in the household, maternal and child<br>home care practices, infant and child feeding, and communication<br>between health workers and women, parents and caregivers.<br>Digital targeted client  54.  WHO recommends digital targeted client communication for  Context-specific<br>communication [22] behaviour change regarding sexual, reproductive, maternal, newborn  recommendation<br>and child health, under the condition that concerns about sensitive<br>content and data privacy are adequately addressed.<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\ng  Including promotion of the following: postnatal care, family planning (distribution of condoms [male and female] and other barrier methods, initiation and distribution of combined oral contraceptives, progestin-only oral contraceptives and emergency contraception, and information and general instructions on the Standard Days Method, TwoDay Method® and the lactational amenorrhoea method), postpartum HIV catch-up testing and retesting, sleeping under insecticide-treated nets, nutritional advice, nutritional supplements, basic newborn care, exclusive breastfeeding and immunization according to national guidelines.\nh  Including: initiate and maintain injectable contraceptives using a standard syringe with needle for intramuscular or subcutaneous injection, insertion of intrauterine device (IUDs), insertion of contraceptive implants.\n> 17 Integrated from the 2016 _WHO recommendations on antenatal care for a positive pregnancy experience_ .\n> 18 Adapted and integrated from the 2012 WHO publication _Optimizing health worker roles to improve access to key maternal and newborn health interventions through