  "SRC002_CHUNK_2_11_0_0": "# Perinatal mental health\n## ANNEX 1",
  "SRC002_CHUNK_2_11_1_0": "## ANNEX 1\n### Sample terms of reference for a working team",
  "SRC002_CHUNK_2_11_1_1": "### Sample terms of reference for a working team\n#### 1. Purpose\n- 1.1 The working team leads the planning and implementation of integration of perinatal mental health (PMH) care into maternal and child health services. It oversees progress in planning and implementation milestones and deliverables. It acts as the decision-making body.",
  "SRC002_CHUNK_2_11_1_2": "### Sample terms of reference for a working team\n#### 2.  Terms of reference\n- 2.1  To advocate for and champion integration of PMH into existing maternal and child services\n- 2.2  To support development of action plans, policies and protocols to integrate PMH into maternal and child services\n- 2.3  To support development of monitoring systems to collect data on PMH\n- 2.4  To support resource mobilization for services and allocate human, financial and technical resources.\n- 2.5  To develop a training plan to build capacity to respond to PMH\n- 2.6  To facilitate multi-sectoral coordination and collaboration with other services and organizations\n- 2.7  To report to senior management on the performance of the programme in addressing PMH",
  "SRC002_CHUNK_2_12_0_0": "# Perinatal mental health\n## 3.  Membership\n- 3.1 Chair: (Name)\n- 3.2  Members: (Names)",
  "SRC002_CHUNK_2_12_1_0": "## 3.  Membership\n### 4.  Decisions\n- 4.1 (Insert details of how decision will be made by the group)",
  "SRC002_CHUNK_2_12_1_1": "### 4.  Decisions\n#### 5.  Meetings\n- 5.1 (Insert details of the frequency, location, hosts and dates of meetings)",
  "SRC002_CHUNK_2_12_1_2": "### 4.  Decisions\n#### 6.  Communications\n- 6.1 (Insert details of the format and anticipated frequency of communication between meetings)\n53",
  "SRC002_CHUNK_2_12_1_3": "### 4.  Decisions\n#### ANNEX 2 Sample template for a budget\nDevelopment of a budget requires estimates of the costs of providing services and identification of sources of funds to cover those costs.\nThe template below gives examples of the items that should be considered in budgeting (see Table A1.1).",
  "SRC002_CHUNK_2_12_1_4": "### 4.  Decisions\n#### **Table A1.1. Sample template for a budget**\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nItem Quantity Unit cost Total cost<br>Workforce: Service management and administration (salaries; a percentage of time if they do not work<br>only for the programme)<br>Workforce: service provider salaries (percentage of time spent by non-dedicated staff)<br>Workforce: training costs (initial)<br>Workforce: training costs (refresher)<br>Workforce: expert technical support<br>Workforce: supervision and mentoring visits<br>Workforce: recruitment costs (if new service providers are to be hired)<br>Meetings with stakeholders (planning and coordination, including venue, stationery, refreshments, etc.)<br>Space renovation (if necessary, to increase privacy or to add space)<br>Computer hardware, software<br>Internet, communications<br>Clinical supplies and equipment<br>Drugs and commodities<br>Advocacy and outreach<br>Producing, printing and dissemination of communication materials<br>Resources to collect, analyse and disseminate results of monitoring and evaluation<br>Insurance<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n54",
  "SRC002_CHUNK_2_12_1_5": "### 4.  Decisions\n#### ANNEX 3 Examples of indicators for monitoring and evaluation\nThe monitoring and evaluation (M&E) plan should have indicators to measure progress towards achieving objectives. The table below provides examples of outputs, the indicators of achievement of the output and the source used to verify the indicator. Each service should select the indicators that are important or measurable in the local setting. Measurements may be quantitative (how many) and qualitative (how well).\n**Table A1.2. Examples of M&E plan**\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nOutput Indicator Source<br>Situational analysis • Situational analysis conducted • Situational analysis report<br>Standard operating procedure for  • No. of standard operating procedures developed and implemented • Standard operating procedure<br>maternal mental health service<br>components<br>Enhanced provision of mental  • No. of facilities and community programmes that provide mental health care • Service use records from<br>health care in MCH services • Proportion of clients with mental health conditions identified and treated  health information systems<br>• Attendance registers<br>Mental health promotion and  • No. of people reached by awareness-raising activities • Community survey on change<br>awareness raising • No. of awareness-raising activities held in knowledge and attitudes<br>• No. of psycho-educational materials distributed • Activity reports<br>• Proportion of clients reached by awareness-raising activities • Satisfaction survey, client<br>• Client satisfaction with awareness-raising activities feedback<br>• Observation by supervisors<br>Screening and detection • No. of clients who booked at the facility and followed the programme • Facility data<br>• No. of clients who were offered screening • Service screening log<br>• No. of clients screened • Observation by supervisors of<br>• Screening coverage (no. of clients screened / no. of clients attending) how well screening is being<br>• Numbers and proportions of clients who: conducted<br>– refused screening<br>– qualified for referral<br>– refused referral<br>– were referred to other services<br>Social support • No. of new clients attending social support service • Social support provider<br>• No. of appointments booked records<br>• No. of appointments attended • Satisfaction survey, client<br>• No. of appointments rescheduled feedback<br>• No. of follow-up appointments missed • Supervisor’s review of case<br>• No. of clients referred to additional services management<br>• Proportion of clients who reported decreased symptoms and improved<br>functioning because of the service<br>• Client satisfaction with the social support provided<br>Psychological intervention • No. of new clients attending a psychological intervention • Counsellor’s diary<br>• No. of appointments booked • Client evaluation records, data<br>• No. of appointments attended (may be broken down by type of appointment:  on repeat screening<br>full, half, face-to-face; digital) • Satisfaction survey, client<br>• No. of appointments rescheduled feedback<br>• No. of follow-up appointments missed • Supervisor’s review of case<br>• No. of clients referred to additional services management<br>• Proportion of clients who reported decreased symptoms and improved<br>functioning because of the service<br>• Client satisfaction with the psychological intervention provided<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n55\n**Table A1.2.** _continued_\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nOutput Indicator Source<br>Medication • No. of new clients seen by prescriber • Psychiatric and mental health<br>• No. of appointments booked service diaries<br>• No. of appointments attended • Medication supply records<br>• No. of appointments rescheduled • Satisfaction survey, client<br>• No. of follow-up appointments missed feedback<br>• Types of medication prescribed<br>• No. or proportion of clients who adhered to medication at 3 months, 6 months<br>and longer<br>• No. of medications in stock<br>• Client satisfaction with the medication provided<br>Training • No. of workshops and training opportunities held • Training logs<br>• No. of trainees who attended • Training evaluation forms<br>• No. of trainers and supervisors who attended training of trainers and of  • Competence assessment<br>supervisors forms and tasks<br>• Trainee feedback and satisfaction<br>• No. of non-specialist trainees trained to meet competence standards<br>Provider supervision • No. of supervisors trained • Supervision notes<br>• No. of supervision sessions held per month (frequency as per standard  • Group supervision attendance<br>operating procedure) forms<br>Coordination of care pathways • No. of facilities, organizations and programmes with procedures for referring or  • Service utilization records<br>receiving women with mental health conditions and psychosocial needs • Facility referral records<br>• No. of referrals and back-referrals made monthly<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n_Source:_ Programme reporting standards for sexual, reproductive, maternal, newborn, child and adolescent health. Geneva: World Health Organization; 2017 (WHO/MCA/17.11).\nGuide for integration of perinatal mental health in maternal and child health services\n56\nFor more information\nDepartment of Mental Health and Substance Use World Health Organization Avenue Appia 20 1211 Geneva 27 Switzerland\nwww.who.int",
