  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_45_1_0": "## TABLE OF\n### **CONTENTS**\n|**CONTENTS**||\n|---|---|\n|Diet and Lifestyle in the Postpartum Period|4|\n|Weight Loss Recommendations for Breastfeeding and Non-Breastfeeding Mothers       5||\n|Dietary Recommendations for Postpartum Women|6|\n|3.1.<br>For breastfeeding mothers|6|\n|3.2.<br>For mothers who are not breastfeeding: nutritional needs|18|\n|3.3.<br>For mothers who had gestational diabetes|18|\n|Physical Activity Recommendations for Postpartum Mothers<br>|19|\n|Your Sleep in the Postpartum Months|22|\n|Your Mental Health in the Postpartum Period<br>|23|\n|6.1.<br>Postpartum depression|23|\n|6.2.<br>Fathers’ support during the postpartum period|24|\n|6.3.<br>Family support in the postpartum period|25|\n|6.4.<br>Eating disorders during the postpartum period|25|\n|Importance of Medical Follow-Up in the Post-Partum Period<br>|26|\n|Appendix 1:||\n|General Recommendations, Serving Examples, And Practical Tips For An||\n|Adequate And Balanced Diet<br>|27|\n|References|34|\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n01<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_45_1_1": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### **Diet and Lifestyle in the Postpartum Period**\nYour postpartum diet and lifestyle are vital for you and your baby. Adopting a healthy diet and lifestyle will help you achieve better physical and mental health during this critical period. It will also help you lose the excess weight you have gained throughout pregnancy which decreases your risk of obesity, type II diabetes and cardiovascular diseases[[1]] .\nAdopting a healthy diet and lifestyle postpartum will also help you provide optimal care for your baby and support adequate breastfeeding. This, in turn, provides your baby with the best nutrition and all the essential nutrients they need[[2]] . This chapter provides information on the appropriate strategies to maintain a healthy diet and lifestyle after childbirth.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_45_1_2": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### **02 Weight Loss Recommendations for Breastfeeding and Non-Breastfeeding Mothers**\nIt is natural to feel eager to lose your pregnancy weight after childbirth. Remember that immediately after delivery, you will lose approximately 6 kg (including your baby’s weight, ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ��������������������������������������������������������������������[ [3]] . If you are breastfeeding ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� because some of the fat stored in your body during pregnancy and the energy from the food you eat, will be utilized for breastmilk production.\n����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� loss goals depend on whether you are overweight or obese or have gained a lot of weight during pregnancy. You need to consult with a dietitian to develop your weight loss plan. In any case, extreme energy restriction and quick weight loss should be avoided. Box 1 provides some general weight loss recommendations, whether you are breastfeeding your baby or not[[3-5]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_45_1_3": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### Box 1. Weight loss recommendations for breastfeeding and non-breastfeeding mothers\nFollowing a healthy diet and exercising will help you lose up to 0.5 kg/week:\n- However, it may take up to 6 months to a year to return to your pre-pregnancy weight, regardless of whether you are breastfeeding or not.\n- If you are breastfeeding, it is not advisable that you lose weight quickly. So do not lose more than 2 kg/month.\nMaking the right food and beverage choices is critical in promoting healthy weight loss:\n- �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������\n- �����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������\n- Choose low-fat milk and dairy products\n- �����������������������������������������������������������\n- Limit your intake of sugar, salt, and unhealthy fats\n- Limit your consumption of high sugar foods (sweets, desserts, candies, confectioneries, �����������������\n- Limit your consumption of fried foods and fast food\n- Control portion sizes\nBe active and incorporate exercise into your weekly lifestyle. Refer to section 4.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n03<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_46_0_0": "## **Dietary Recommendations for Postpartum Women**",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_46_1_0": "## **Dietary Recommendations for Postpartum Women**\n### 3.1. For breastfeeding mothers\nis a representation of the main dietary recommendations if you are breastfeeding.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nEnergy needs:<br>Consult with your  Add 330 kcal/day during<br>physician regarding taking<br>supplements Add 440 kcal/day during<br>the second 6 months<br>FOR<br>BREASTFEEDING<br>MOTHERS<br>Avoid harmful substances  Follow a balanced and<br>(such as smoking) adequate diet<br>Water: Increase your<br>water intake by 1 liter per<br>day compared to  when you<br>were not breastfeeding<br>6<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_46_1_1": "### 3.1. For breastfeeding mothers\n#### **1. Energy needs:**\nThe general dietary intake recommendations for women are shown in Appendix 1.  The same ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� you will need to take some additional energy when you are breastfeeding, as follows:\n- An additional **�������������������������������������������������������** compared to non-breastfeeding women.\n- An additional **���������������������������������������������������������** compared to non-breastfeeding women[[6, 7]] .\nBox 2 below presents examples of food choices that can provide you with this additional amount of energy during breastfeeding. **�������������������������������������������������������� ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� consume from each food group.**\nBox 2. Examples of snacks that could be added to your diet to meet your additional energy needs during breastfeeding",
