  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_70_1_0": "## TABLE OF\n### **CONTENTS**\n||**CONTENTS**||\n|---|---|---|\n|01|Assessment Of The Child’s Growth|6|\n|02|Continued Breastfeeding (For Up To Two Years And Beyond)<br>|7|\n|03|Dietary Recommendations|8|\n|04|What Are The Signs To Start The Complementary Feeding (Weaning) Process?       9||\n|05|How To Start The Complementary Feeding (Weaning) Process?<br>|10|\n|06|Food Consistency (Texture)|11|\n|07|Introduction Of Soft, Semi-Solid And Solid Foods|12|\n|08|Hunger & Satiety Cues|17|\n|09|How To Boost My Child’s Immunity|18|\n|10|Picky Eating<br>|19|\n|11|Force-Feeding|24|\n|12|Choking Hazards In Young Children|25|\n|13|Are There Any Foods My Baby Should Not Eat?|27|\n|14|How To Prepare Foods For Your Baby|29|\n|15|Oral Health<br>|40|\n|16|Supplements<br>|41|\n|17|Food Allergies|42|\n|18|Food Safety Considerations|48|\n|Food Safety Considerations<br>|48|\n|---|---|\n|Physical Activity Recommendations For Infants And Young Children<br>|49|\n|Appendix 1:||\n|����������������������������������������������������|��|\n|Appendix 2:||\n|General Food Safety Considerations|55|\n|References|58|\nAt around six months of age, your baby will need to consume healthy and nutritious foods, in addition to breastmilk, to meet his/her energy and nutrient needs. Therefore, at six months, solid foods, such as vegetables, fruits, infant cereals, and mashed meat, should be introduced to complement your child’s diet while maintaining breastfeeding for up to two years and beyond[ [1]] .\n����������������������������������������������������������������������� 1000 days of life, and is a critical period for your child’s growth and development for his/her future health. It is also the period when malnutrition may start to develop in many children[ [2]] , which can have ������������������������������������������������������������������ can lead to delayed physical and mental development, decreased intellectual performance, and poor health later on during adolescence and adulthood. Once a child reaches two ���������������������������������������������� �����������������������������������[[3]] .\n“The transition from exclusive breastfeeding to family foods, referred to as complementary feeding, typically covers the period from 6 to 18 - 24 months of age.”\n-World Health Organization (WHO)[[4]        ]\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n01 Assessment of the  Child’s Growth<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nIt is important that the doctor routinely assesses the growth of your child. Growth is, in fact, an important indicator of the child’s overall health, development, and nutritional status. the doctor ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� age of your child[[5-7]] .\nIn some instances, these measurements may reveal certain growth-related problems, such as:\n- The child has a low weight for his/her age (underweight or severely underweight): This may result from the child being too thin or too short for his/her age. It may also be the result of poor nutrition or certain illnesses. Underweight children are more vulnerable to diseases and may experience delays in their development.\n- The child is short for his/her age (stunted or severely stunted): If your child’s height is below the normal range for his/her age (a condition referred to as stunting), this may be the result of long-term malnutrition or illness. It has consequences on the child’s physical development and is often accompanied by poor mental development.\n- The child has lost weight (wasted or severely wasted): This may occur because of poor nutrition or illness. Wasted children have a higher risk of contracting diseases and illnesses.\n- The child is overweight or obese: Infants and young children can become overweight or obese ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� genetic factors (i.e., running in the family), or a combination of all these factors. In rare cases, obesity in children may result from a medical condition diagnosed by the doctor. Being overweight and obese early in life can increase the risk of obesity and chronic diseases later in life.\n- The child has a larger-than-normal or smaller-than-normal head circumference: This helps in assessing brain size as an indicator of possible developmental or nutritional problems.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n02 Continued Breastfeeding<br>(for Up to Two Years and Beyond)<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nFor optimal growth and development, the World Health Organization (WHO) and United Nations International Children’s Emergency Fund (UNICEF) recommend continued breastfeeding for up to two years and beyond while introducing adequate complementary foods (solid and soft foods) at six months of age.\n����������������������������������������������������������������������[ [8-10]]\n- Breastmilk provides your baby with important nutrients (but make sure to introduce solid foods in addition to breastmilk at six months of age).\n- Breastmilk strengthens your child’s immunity; as long as you breastfeed your baby, the antibodies and cells in your breastmilk will continue to enhance your baby’s immune system.\nIn addition, breastfeeding reduces your risk of certain illnesses, such as the risk of developing ovarian cancer, breast cancer, high blood pressure, heart disease, type 2 diabetes and rheumatoid arthritis.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n03<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_70_1_1": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### **Dietary Recommendations**\nAdequate child growth depends on several factors, including appropriate energy and nutrient intake. Starting complementary feeding is a must at six months since milk alone will not meet all ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ of nutrient-dense foods from the following general food groups:\n- Breastmilk (or infant formula milk in certain conditions)\n- Vegetables:\n- Vitamin A rich vegetables such as pumpkin, carrots, sweet red peppers, squash, and dark green leafy vegetables.\n- Other vegetables such as broccoli, zucchini and cucumbers. Try to choose vegetables ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� vitamins and minerals.\n- Fruits:\n- Vitamin A rich fruits such as ripe mangoes and ripe papayas.\n- ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������\n- �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� and potatoes.\n- Legumes: such as beans and lentils.\n- Dairy products: such as yogurt, labneh and cheese.\n- �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� eggs.\nSection 6 provides information on the texture (consistency) ����������������������������������������������������������\nSection 12 provides details on what foods to avoid to prevent choking and tips on how to prepare these foods.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n04<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n**What are the Signs to Start the Complementary Feeding (Weaning) Process?**\n������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ complementary feeding[[11]] :\n- Your baby can stay in a sitting position with their head held steady with no support\n- Your baby has full coordination between their eyes, hands, and mouth by locating the food and attempting to pick it up to place in their mouth.\n- Your baby can properly swallow their food and not spit it out\n- Your baby seems hungry earlier than usual\n- Your baby shows interest in food when others are eating\n- Your baby can let you know if they do not want to eat by turning their head away from the food or leaning back\n- Your baby’s weight has doubled compared to their birth weight.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n05<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_70_1_2": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### **How to Start the Complementary Feeding (Weaning) Process?**\nAs previously mentioned, complementary feeding should begin at six months of age; however, the weaning process could take days, weeks, or months depending on your baby’s growth and development[[12]] . You can begin by slowly decreasing how often or how long you are breastfeeding and/or formula feeding each day.  Begin with substituting one breastfeed with complementary feed, and once your baby is accustomed to this, you can substitute another feed, and so on. Remember that the weaning process should be gradual, and the pace is up to you and your baby[[12]] .\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n06 Food Consistency (Texture)<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nIt is recommended to gradually thicken food consistency as the baby ages, while paying attention to your baby’s abilities. Infants can usually eat puréed, mashed and soft/semi-solid ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� (i.e., foods and snacks that the baby can grasp and eat alone).\nBy the age of 12 months, most children can consume the same types of foods as the rest of the family (while making sure that these are nutritious foods)[[4, 13]] . Refer to section 12 to learn more about the risk of choking and how to avoid it, and to section 14 for examples of nutritious foods and tips on preparing foods for your baby.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_71_0_0": "## **07 Introduction of Soft, Semi-Solid and Solid Foods**",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_71_1_0": "## **07 Introduction of Soft, Semi-Solid and Solid Foods**\n### **�������������������������������������������������**\n���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� to keep them plain (i.e., no added salt, sugar, or strong spices).\n��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� However, many experts agree that you should start with foods that contain iron, since it is needed for many areas of the baby’s development[[11]] ������������������������������������������ �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� (such as rice and oatmeal), vegetables, and fruits are also good sources of iron and other vital minerals and vitamins.\nIt is very important that you introduce one single-ingredient food to your baby at a time. For example, introduce peaches alone rather than peach-yogurt, which has more than one ingredient. Introducing a single new food at a time, at 3-5 days intervals, will allow you to  identify any adverse reaction, allergic response or intolerances that your baby may have to certain foods[ [11]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_71_1_1": "### **�������������������������������������������������**\n#### **6-8 months**\nAt around six months of age, you can introduce strained or puréed foods to your baby’s diet (see �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� your baby directly from a squeezable pouch.\nSome dietitians recommend introducing vegetables before fruits. This is because the sweetness of fruits will make vegetables less ������������������������������� �����\n“Your baby needs more energy and nutrients now than at any other time in their life.”\n-UNICEF[[14]                          ]\n�����������������������������������������������������",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_71_1_2": "### **�������������������������������������������������**\n#### **�����������������������������������������������������[[11]] :**\n- Well-cooked mashed vegetables, puréed meat, well-cooked mashed legumes (e.g., beans, lentils, peas (peeled), rice, mashed potatoes, and whole-fat dairy products (such as yogurt)\n- Soft, diced, or mashed fruits such as bananas , apples (puréed after boiling), ripe mangos, avocados, and melons\n- ��������������������������\n- All foods should be natural without the addition of salt, sugar, or spices\nIntroduce a single new food at a time, at 3-5 day-intervals. This approach will allow you to identify any adverse reaction, allergic response or intolerances that your baby may have to �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������\nExamples   of nutritious, suitable, and easy to prepare meals for your baby (6-8 months old):\n- Puréed: potatoes + carrots + peas, mashed with fork (without salt)\n- Puréed: potatoes + carrots + peas, mashed with fork + boiled chicken\n- Puréed: potatoes + carrots + peas, mashed with fork + part of boiled egg\n- Pumped breastmilk or formula milk + mashed boiled rice (without salt)\n- Mashed lentil soup: rice + mashed lentils + potatoes + carrots\n- Mashed: boiled rice + spinach, mulukhiya (jute leaves), beans, or basil (without salt)\n- Puréed: Apples (boiled, yellow, or green, or red), ripe\n- Mashed bananas and avocado\nIf you have to use ready-made foods, read the nutrition label and buy high-quality, natural baby foods that do not contain unhealthy fats, added sugar, salt,  or chemical preservatives[[15]] .\n���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� add enough breast milk or formula to the infant cereal (do not use cow’s milk) for a relatively thin consistency so that it is easy for your baby to swallow. Just 2 feedings a day, a couple of spoonfuls, is all your baby needs[[11]] .\nWhen introducing store-bought infant cereals, check the food label to ensure that the cereal is a single-ingredient product and does not contain other added ingredients such as cow’s milk, ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� reactions to the cereals (See section 17 on food allergies and section 14 on tips related to preparing foods for your baby).",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_71_1_3": "### **�������������������������������������������������**\n#### **How much food should I give my baby?**\n- Complementary feeding should be introduced at six months, however most of your baby’s daily calories will still come from breastmilk (or formula) at this age. Once you start introducing complementary feeding, your baby may only be eating one meal per day along with breastmilk (or formula). This is completely normal; start slowly and progressively increase the number of meals daily.\n- Eventually, you can give 3 meals per day to your 6-8 months old baby, with an amount close to 2-3 tablespoons of food per meal[ [16]] , while maintaining breastfeeding (or formula ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� his/her appetite.\n- Observe your child for signs of hunger or satiety (see section 8)[[16]] .\n- If you are formula feeding, do not exceed more than 950 mL (32 oz.) in 24 hours[[11]] . Overfeeding can cause vomiting, diarrhea, or excessive weight gain.\nAn example of choices to include in a one-day menu is provided in Box 2[[17]] .\n|Box 2. Example of choices to include in a one-day menu (while continuing breastmilk or|Box 2. Example of choices to include in a one-day menu (while continuing breastmilk or|\n|---|---|\n|formula feeding)||\n|**Mealtimes**|**Sample Meals**|\n|Breakfast|�����������������������������|\n||Strawberries or blueberries, mashed|\n|Lunch|Boiled chicken|\n||Boiled chickpeas, mashed|\n|Snack|Ripe pear, peeled and mashed|\n|Dinner|Ground beef or well-cooked mashed lentils|\n||Boiled rice|\n||Boiled broccoli, mashed|",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_71_1_4": "### **�������������������������������������������������**\n#### **9-12 months:**\n- ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� foods in small amounts. Your baby will show signs that they are ready to eat on their own by trying to grab the food or the spoon with their hands.\n- �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� as fruits)[[16]] . Per meal, your baby can consume an amount of food equivalent to ½ cup (i.e., approximately 125 mL)[[16]] .\n- ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� made it to their mouth. Your baby is learning, and he/she will soon be able to get the skills ���������������������������������������������������������������������[[18]] .\n�����������������������������������������������������������\n- Allowing your child to feed themselves is the best technique to allow them to experience their senses such as taste, texture and smell.\n- Nurturing independence (giving them a little control over when they take a bite, how much they put in their mouth, and when they are done eating).\n- Enhancing grasping and coordination skills.\n- Allowing them to be aware of their bodies (knowing where their mouth is, how to bend �������������������������������������������������\n- Helping in oral motor development (how wide they need to open their mouth, close their ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_71_1_5": "### **�������������������������������������������������**\n#### **12-24 months:**\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ per day at 12-24 months of age, with additional nutritious snacks (such as a piece of fruit), 1-2 times per day[[16]] .\n- Per meal, your child can consume an amount close to ¾  cup, i.e. around 190 mL[[16]] . Appendix 1 provides information on the recommended number of servings from each food group, and examples of servings.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nChildren do not need to<br>eat chocolate or sweets to feel<br>���������������������������������������<br> IMPORTANT they need from a healthy and varied<br>NOTE diet that includes food and beverages<br>from the six food groups (refer to<br>Appendix 1).<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n08 Hunger and Satiety Cues<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nFeed your child at his or her own comfort and observe signs of hunger and satiety (feeling of fullness). Below are hunger and satiety cues that your child may display (Box 4)[[19]] .",
