  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_1": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **Satiety cues**\n- Moves head towards spoon/food, bottle, or nipple\n- Smiles during feeding to indicate they want more\n- Points out or reaches for food\n- Gets excited when he/she sees food\n- Expresses with words or sounds the �������������������������\n- Turns head away from spoon/food, bottle, or nipple\n- Spits food out of their mouth\n- Shakes head to say no more\n- Clenches mouth, closes and refuses to open\n- Plays with the food, spoon, or plate\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n09<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_2": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **How to Boost My Child’s Immunity**\nChildren need adequate intakes of nutrients and vitamins to help boost their immune system and protect them against infectious germs. However, there are no magical foods or supplements that will boost your child’s immune system[ [20]] . The best advice for supporting your child’s immunity is ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� a varied and balanced diet consisting of food and beverages from the six food groups.  Prioritize nutrient-rich foods such as vegetables and fruits that supply an abundant amount of antioxidants, vitamins, and minerals. Make sure to limit their consumption of processed foods, snacks, and foods high in sugar, salt, and unhealthy fats. Consult Appendix 1 for details pertinent to dietary recommendations for your child.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n10 Picky Eating<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nSome children go through a phase of refusing certain types of food, especially when trying �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� occurs among young children and is often perceived as a stressful and frustrating experience for parents. Picky eating rarely causes serious nutritional, medical or growth problems for the child, and it is a phase that most children grow out of[[21]] ����������������������������������������� habits, and they can be considered as “extreme picky eaters.” Professionals may consider this as a feeding disorder, and you will need the help of a health professional to help your child grow out of �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������[[21]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_3": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **Picky eaters & extreme picky eaters**\nExtreme picky eating can last for a longer time as compared to picky eating. Extreme picky eaters can grow out of it over months or years; however, this usually needs to be done with the help of a health professional[ [21]] . Extreme picky eating is usually more common in children with social communication disorders[[21]] .\nAlthough being a picky eater is usually harmless, being an extreme picky eater can cause serious �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������[ [21]] . Table 1 provides you with a direct comparison between the two behaviors.\nTable 1. Comparison between picky eating and extreme picky eating characteristics in children ����������������������\n||**Picky eating**|**Extreme picky eating**|\n|---|---|---|\n|How common|• Very common in children.|• Less common.|\n|is it?|• ��������������������������������|• More common in children with social|\n|||communication disorders.|\n|Health/Growth|• No health/growth consequences or|• Moderate to severe health/growth|\n|consequences|only minor ones.|consequences.|\n|||• However, in some cases, there is no|\n|||health/growth consequences or only|\n|||minor ones.|\n|Impact on parents|• Can be very stressful for parents.|• Usually very stressful for parents.|\n|Do children grow|• Usually, children grow out of it within|• Can take a longer time (months or|\n|out of it?|a period of weeks to months.|years) for children to grow out of it.|\n|||• Management requires the help of a|\n|||health professional.|\n|Eating habits|• They eat a range of food items, with|• They eat a limited range of food|\n||a preference for some food items|�������������������������������|\n||from each food group.|types.|\n||• Some days, they may only eat|• They often exclude some food groups|\n||very little or have preferences for|altogether.|\n||�������������������������������||\n|Feelings towards|• Picky eaters are upset when new|• Extreme picky eaters are upset|\n|new food items|food items are introduced and their|when new food items are introduced|\n||������������������������|and when their favorite food is not|\n|||��������������������������������|\n|||be more extreme.|\n|Hiding food in|• You can sometimes hide the refused|• �������������������������|\n|other food items|food item in other foods that the|because the child can detect it.|\n||child likes.||\n|Would they eat|• They would eventually eat the|• ���������������������������|\n|������������|����������������������������|usually, and they may be at risk of|\n|hungry?|themselves.|being ill from starving themselves[21].|",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_4": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **When to seek professional help?**\nDo not get frustrated if your child is a picky eater. Just provide your child with healthy food choices and try your best to help your child grow out of this phase. Most picky eaters remain healthy, and their eating habits tend to gradually improve as they age[ [22]] . If your child’s picky ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������[ [21]] .\nBox 5 provides some useful steps to follow if your child is a picky eater[[21-23]] .\n|Box 5. Steps to follow with your “picky eater” child|Box 5. Steps to follow with your “picky eater” child|Box 5. Steps to follow with your “picky eater” child|\n|---|---|---|\n|Establish a||• �����������������������������������������������������������������|\n|clear eating||something nutritious every 2-3 hours).|\n|routine||• ���������������������������������������������������������������|\n|||appetite.|\n|||• Mealtime should be around 20-30 minutes. Do not rush your child to eat.|\n|||• Your child should eat meals and snacks sitting down in a comfortable place.|\n|||• Involve the child in the routine. For example, after washing their hands, they can|\n|||help you prepare the table and at the end of the meal they can help you clear it.|\n|Limit beverage<br>consumption<br>at mealtime||• �������������������������������������������������������������<br>end of the meal/snack.|\n|||• �����������������������������������������������������������|\n|Encourage||• Eat together as a family as often as you can. Be a role model and eat with your|\n|a healthy||child because children imitate their parents.|\n|attitude||• Let your child enjoy eating with other children.|\n|towards||• ������������������������������������������������������������������|\n|eating||them to try it.|\n|||• Encourage your child to eat but never force them to eat.|\n|||• Let your child learn to eat to their appetite; do not force them to eat more than|\n|||they can or to clear their plates.|\n|||• Try to always have a calm and relaxed environment when eating.|\n|||• Your child should eat meals and snacks while sitting in a comfortable place.|\n|||• Avoid anything that can distract the child from eating such as television,|\n|||electronic devices, and toys. The child’s attention should be focused on the|\n|||eating experience.|\n|||• �����������������������������������������������������������������|\n|||�������������������������������������������������������������|\n|||������������������������������������������������������������|\n|||child accepts it.|\n|||• Divide each main meal into 2 courses: a savory main course and a healthy|\n|||dessert. Examples of a healthy dessert include a fresh whole fruit, fruit salad,|\n|||or a yogurt.|\n- Do not use desserts as a reward for eating other foods; this approach will make desserts more exciting for them and, as a result, may impact their acceptance of other foods.\n- Encourage good behavior at mealtime by rewarding the child with “non-food” items.\n- • Verbal praise or a loving look are considered positive in developing food preferences.\n- Decide what ������������� • ������������������������������������������������������������ child ���������������������������������������������� • ����������������������������������������������������������� if possible. But make sure that it is suitable for the child’s age (such as mashed, chopped, etc.).\n- Try adding herbs and spices to make the food tastier for the child.\n- �������������������������������������������������������������� ���������������������������������������������������\n- ������������������������������������������������������ again.\n- �������������������������������������������������������������� and appropriate to their needs.\n- ����������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������� preference.\n- • Try to mix the new food item with a food the child likes. For example, adding mashed peas to mashed potatoes.\n- • When the child accepts new food items, use these items as ������������������������������������������������������������� color, and texture. For example, if your child likes mashed ���������������������������������������������������������� or carrots.\n- • Encourage children to feed themselves as much as possible �������������������������������������������������������������� them to acquire self-feeding skills and thus become more independent.\n- Stick to your plan • Many children go through a picky eating phase which usually causes no harm. Try not to overthink it and do your best to help them grow out of it.\n- • ����������������������������������������������������������� accepts it. Young children are naturally cautious when trying ��������������������������������������������������������������\n- Do NOT • Do NOT count calories or weigh your child daily. • Do NOT label your child as “the picky eater.” • Do NOT lower expectations by assuming or telling your child “You won’t like anything.”\n- • Do NOT complain about your child’s eating behavior in front of them.\n- • Do NOT inspect your child’s lunchbox or ask about their food intake the moment you see them.\n- • Do NOT punish or scold your child for not eating.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n11 Force-Feeding<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nParents tend to get worried when their child eats very little, refuses to eat a meal or refuses to eat healthy foods like fruits and vegetables[[24]] ������������������������������������������������� especially if the child is underweight or not gaining weight adequately. For others, unconsumed meals can be a source of frustration, especially when the parents do not like to waste food that has been prepared, or when they believe that children have to ‘clean their plates’[[24]] . As a result, parents may force their child to eat their entire meal.\nThe child may indeed eat a bit more when forced to eat. However, studies have shown that the act of forcing the child to eat can cause long-term problems, which are summarized below:\n- **Disliking or avoiding certain foods.** This can result from a negative experience of being ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� and unpleasant experiences that may accompany them[ [24]] .\n- **Disturbing the child’s ability to respond to their internal feelings of hunger and fullness.** This means that the child would not listen to their body, so food intake becomes determined by factors other than what the body requires. Instead, the child learns to continue eating, even when they feel full, stopping only when the plate is empty[[24]] .\n- **Development of overeating and overweight.** As explained above, forcing the child to eat can disturb the child’s ability to learn appropriate appetite control. This can eventually lead to overeating and the development of overweight and obesity[[24]] .\nExcept in rare cases, children are usually extremely good at knowing when they are full and ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ they will eat when feeling hungry. It is also important to remember that children naturally tend ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� and accept that children may refuse to eat it, as this is a normal part of their development. Also remember that the stomachs of young children are smaller than adults’ and you may be serving too much food that your child cannot consume.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n12 Choking Hazards in Young Children<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_5": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **What are the choking hazards for 6-12 months old babies?**\nYoung children are at a risk of food-related choking. Even if they started developing teeth, this ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������\n- ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� vegetables, whole cherry tomatoes, raw apple slices, raw pear slices, whole kernels of corn, and whole olives. (Note: carrots and corn, can be cooked and then diced).\n- Slippery foods: including whole small fruits, such as grapes, berries and cherries, large pieces of meat, poultry and cheese, hot dogs, and hard candy such as lollipops, jellybeans, and cough drops. (Note: meat, poultry and other protein foods should be well-cooked and then cut lengthwise or chopped up into smaller pieces (less than 0.5 cm in size). Grapes should be cut into quarters.)\n- Sticky foods:������������������������������������������������������������������������� jellybeans, dried fruits, and fruit leathers. (Note: smooth nut butters should be spread in a thin layer on a food, such as bread; they should not be given straight from a spoon or a �������\n- Fruits with seeds or stones: whole fruits with stones inside such as cherries, plum, etc.\n- Foods that can form crumbs in your baby’s mouth include bread, hard cookies/biscuits.\n**Tips to keep your baby safe from choking**\n- �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� can mash them with their tongue on the top of their mouth).\n- Cut potentially hazardous foods into smaller bite-sized pieces.\n- Supervise your child during all meal and snack times.\n- Do not let other children feed your child unless they are supervised closely.\n- Encourage your child to chew their food well before swallowing\n- Your baby should always be sitting upright when eating, never leaning backwards, or laying down.\n- Your child should not be walking or running while eating\n- Let your baby eat at their own pace and let them put the food into their mouth.\n- Vacuum and sweep regularly to remove choking hazards in the home.\n- Remove any unsafe food or toys from your child’s reach.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_6": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **What are choking hazards for children 12 to 24 months old?**\nMost of your baby’s teeth would have already come in at this age, making chewing and swallowing a lot easier. By now, your child is able to eat most foods, however there are still some choking hazards. How food is prepared, cooked, and served can still impact the incidence of choking. You should therefore still be cutting or mashing certain foods, to prevent choking. Below are examples of foods that are potential choking hazards for your babies between the ages of 12 and 24 months[ [25]] .\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nVegetables and Fruits Cereals & starchy  Fish, poultry, meat and  Sweetened foods<br>vegetables alternatives<br>• Carrot sticks • Chips • Tough meat that  • Chewing gum<br>• Uncut whole  • Popcorn requires back  • Hard candies<br>molars to chew<br>grapes, cherries,<br>blueberries, or  • Round slices of hot<br>cherry tomatoes  dogs or sausages<br>(or any round  • Whole nuts or<br>vegetable/fruit) seeds<br>• Large pieces of raw  • Chunky peanut<br>hard vegetables or  butter<br>fruits<br>26<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_7": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **13 Are There Any Foods My Baby Should Not Eat?**\n- Cow’s milk: ���������������������������������������������������������������������������� infants cannot digest cow’s milk.\n- Honey: Honey should never be given to babies under the age of one year, as there is a risk of infant botulism (food poisoning).\n- Raw or runny eggs:����������������������������������������������������������������� year of life. Runny eggs can contain bacteria such as salmonella that cause food poisoning. ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� poached, boiled, or fried).\n- Camel milk:�������������������������������������������������������������������\n- Goat milk: ����������������������������������������������������������������������������� ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� given to your baby if recommended by the doctor.\n- Sugary drinks or sweet foods: ������������������������������������������������������������ candies, carbonated soda, or energy drinks.\n- Salt: Try to avoid puréeing adult foods and feeding them to your child as they may contain large amounts of salt. Your baby’s kidneys are not yet fully developed to cope with large amounts of salt, and the longer you wait to introduce it into their diet, the better chance you have of not encouraging a liking for it.\n- �������������� Culturally speaking, the older generations have the misconception that if ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� overstimulate your baby and may also prevent the baby’s body from absorbing iron from their food.\n- Low-fat foods (especially dairy products): Low-calorie cheeses, yogurts or spreads should not be given to babies. Always feed your baby the full-fat varieties as their body needs it.\n- Foods that can lead to choking: Foods that may stick to the roof of the mouth and foods ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ section 12 for more information on the risk of choking).\nBeyond six months of age, there is no reason to delay the introduction of common food allergens ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� regularly and monitor if any signs of an allergic reaction occur. If you have concerns, please speak to the doctor.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n14<br>How to Prepare Foods for Your Baby<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nRecommendation 8 of the Qatar Dietary Guidelines (QDG), which is “Take care of your family,” heavily focuses on the following:\n“Build and model healthy patterns for your family”\n- Keep regular hours for meals.\n- Eat at least one meal together with your family every day.\n- Be a role model for your children when it comes to healthy eating and physical activity.\n��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� recommends for healthy adults, the same recommendations can be given here; always limit sugar, salt and unhealthy fats/oils when preparing your baby’s meals and adopt healthier cooking methods such as boiling, steaming, baking and grilling. Do not add sugar, salt, and spices to the child’s food before 12 months of age.\nThe following section presents examples of nutritious foods to introduce to your baby’s diet as well as the cooking/preparation method that will best preserve the foods’ nutritive value. The information is presented per food group.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_8": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **VEGETABLES**\n||This vegetable is high in vitamin C, vitamin K, calcium,|\n|---|---|\n||������������������������������������������������|\n||baby’s bowels, making it easier for them to pass stool. Gently|\n||steam broccoli for 5 minutes or roast them in the oven with|\n|**Broccoli**|a little bit of olive oil for 12-20 minutes or until they are soft|\n||and tender. You can serve them puréed, by placing them in|\n||a blender and adding water if necessary to achieve a smooth|\n||consistency. You can also serve them chopped once your|\n||child starts self-feeding.|\n||���������������������������������������������������|\n||�����������������������������������������������������|\n||folate, vitamin C, vitamin K and minerals, like potassium|\n||������������������������������������������������|\n|**Zucchini**|this veggie into your baby’s diet is that it can help improve<br>digestion and reduce the incidence of constipation. Gently|\n||steam or boil for 2-4 minutes and chop in small cubes or thin|\n||strips. Another way to cook them is to slice them in round|\n||coin shapes and sauté them in a pan with a little bit of olive|\n||oil until they are soft and tender.|\n||Make sure the only peppers your baby is eating are the mild|\n||and sweet peppers (i.e., not the hot ones). Peppers are rich|\n||������������������������������������������������|\n||contains more vitamin C than an orange).|\n|**Bell**<br>**Peppers /**<br>**capsicum**<br>**(red,**|•<br>How you prepare them for your baby depends on<br>the stage of development he/she is in. If your baby is<br>still being spoon-fed, bell peppers are delicious when<br>puréed and super easy to prepare. Just steam them for|\n|**yellow,**|a few minutes to soften them up and throw them in|\n|**orange or**|the blender.|\n|**green)**|•<br>If your baby has reached the stage where they can|\n||�������������������������������������|\n||peppers (if they have teeth) in long slices, or slightly|\n||steamed if they cannot chew properly.|\n||These are an excellent source of lycopene, vitamins A and|\n|**Cherry**|C, and a good source of vitamin K, vitamin E and potassium.<br>Serve them raw but cut into halves, quarters, or eighths|\n|**tomatoes**|(depending on how well your baby can chew to avoid|\n||chances of choking).|\n|||They are one of the sweetest vegetables, and babies will naturally|\n|---|---|---|\n|||������������������������������������������������������|\n|||turns into vitamin A in the body. Vitamin A is the key nutrient|\n|||in developing a strong eyesight. Besides being good for eye|\n|||development, carrots strengthen the immune system and protect|\n|||against heart disease and some types of cancer.|\n|**Carrots**||•<br>Steam or boil carrots until they are tender, or roast them|\n|||in the oven. Serve them chopped into small pieces, cut into|\n|||round pieces or in strips.|\n|||•<br>They can also be puréed. Steam or boil the carrots, throw|\n|||them into a blender, and add water depending on how thick|\n|||you want the consistency to be.|\n|||Though it is widely considered a vegetable, it is a fruit. It is low|\n|||����������������������������������������������������|\n|||����������������������������������������������������������|\n|||baby’s bowl movement and reduce episodes of constipation.|\n|||•<br>If you do not want to purchase a whole pumpkin, many|\n|**Pumpkin**||grocery stores have pre-chopped and packaged pumpkin.<br>To prepare the pumpkin, peel and remove the seeds. You|\n|||can steam, boil, or roast until soft and tender. Chop into|\n|||small cubes and serve plain or add your favorite (non-spicy)|\n|||seasonings.|\n|||•<br>You can also purée the pumpkin.|\n|||������������������������������������������������������|\n|||one. Cucumbers are composed mostly of water as well as a number|\n|||of vitamins and minerals. Fun fact: Cold cucumbers right out of the|\n|**Cucumbers**||fridge (either cut into rings or slices) can be a natural remedy to ease|\n|||or at least distract your baby from teething pain.|\n|||��������������������������������������������������������|\n|||“green” vegetable to introduce into your baby’s diet. Peas are an|\n|||�����������������������������������������������������|\n|||vitamins and minerals. A cup of cooked green peas has around 3.6|\n|||mg of lutein, an antioxidant that aids in maintaining healthy eyes.|\n|**Green**||•<br>When purchasing peas at the grocery store, try to get fresh|\n|**peas**||or frozen ones. Limit canned peas as they are high in sodium<br>due to preservation methods.|\n|||•<br>�����������������������������������������������|\n|||sauté them and serve them with a little bit of freshly squeezed|\n|||�����������������������������|",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_9": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **FRUITS**\nFeeding your baby fresh fruit is quite easy as it requires no cooking and requires very little preparation time.\n|**Strawber-**<br>**ries**||These delicious and nutrient-packed fruits may cause<br>an allergic reaction to some babies, so be careful when<br>introducing them into your baby’s diet. Once you introduce<br>them, monitor if any signs of an allergic reaction occur.<br>Acidic foods such as citrus fruits and berries may cause a<br>rash around your baby’s mouth, which may be an allergic<br>reaction or just an irritation to the acids in the foods[26](see<br>section 17 on allergies for more detailed information). The<br>�����������������������������������������������<br>����������������������������������������������������<br>(strengthens their immunity), antioxidants, promotes healthy<br>eyesight, and help regulate blood sugar levels.<br>•<br>Finely chop or cut into quarters before feeding them to<br>your baby.<br>•<br>����������������������������������������<br>fruit within the berry family such as blueberries,<br>blackberries, and raspberries.|\n|---|---|---|\n|**Oranges**||Although they are known for their richness in vitamin C, this<br>delicious juicy fruit is also packed with many other health<br>������������������������������������������������<br>���������������������������������������������������<br>����������������������������������������������������<br>Once you introduce them to your child’s diet, it is important<br>to monitor if any signs of an allergic reaction occur[27]. The<br>acidic nature of these fruits may sometimes cause a diaper<br>rash and/or may cause redness around the mouth and lips,<br>which may be an allergic reaction or just an irritation to the<br>acids in the foods.<br>•<br>To serve, cut oranges into small bite-size pieces as<br>oranges are soft and slippery so there is a higher risk<br>for larger pieces to slide down your baby’s throat and<br>cause choking.<br>•<br>��������������������������������������������<br>the rind and membrane as your baby may not have the<br>teeth yet to chew them properly.|\n|---|---|---|\nThey say an apple a day, keeps the doctor away. With regards to babies, apples may not protect them from all illnesses they may be exposed to, but they sure can boost immunity as they are packed with vitamin C and can help prevent episodes of constipation which can be quite uncomfortable and painful for your little one. At six months of age, your toddler may not be able to chew apples properly, therefore the best solution is to purée your apples. **Apple** • Cut and peel apples then bring them to a boil in a saucepan. Simmer for about 10 minutes or until the apples are very soft. Allow apples to cool and blend them well (no need to add any ingredients to the purée). • Once your baby has developed teeth and is able to chew properly, you can serve them raw apple slices as a delicious snack. These delicious tropical fruits can be added to your baby’s diet right at six months as they are an excellent source of ��������������������������������������������������������� sweet treat is better eaten ripe, as they require little prep time. • Just mash the mangoes with a fork and they can be eaten on their own or mixed with mashed veggies or other ingredients. **Mangoes** • Try adding mashed or puréed mangoes with any of the following foods: oatmeal, yogurt, avocado, carrot, sweet potato, banana, or apple. • Puréed mangoes can also be frozen for up to three months, so freeze them in small batches and only thaw �������������������������������������������������� eaten on their own.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_10": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **CEREALS & STARCHY VEGETABLES**\nCereals and starchy vegetables provide your baby with a major source of energy (calories) and represent an essential part of a healthy diet to ensure your child’s normal growth and development. Cereals and starchy vegetables are excellent sources of complex �������������������������������������������������������������������������\nThe initial foods introduced within this food group are infant cereals and starchy vegetables such as potatoes and peas. You can mix the infant cereal with your breastmilk, water, or formula (if you were already formula feeding your infant). Make sure the cereal is of thin consistency to allow for easy swallowing. As your baby gets older and develops more motor skills, you can increase the thickness.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_11": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **�����������������������������������������**\n�������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� mostly from the endosperm, therefore they have less nutritional value compared to whole grains.\nBelow is a list of whole grain options for baby food recipes:\n|**Oatmeal**||����������������������|\n|---|---|---|\n|**Rice**||One of the least allergenic grains|\n|**(brown)**|||\n|||Highly nutritious as most pastas in the market are enriched|\n|**Pasta**||with vitamins and minerals. They are an excellent energy|\n|**(brown)**||�������������������������������������������������<br>baby develops motor skills to feed themselves.|\n|||Although most plant-based foods do not contain complete|\n|||proteins (containing all essential amino acids,) quinoa is|\n|**Quinoa**||the exception here. This complete whole grain protein is|\n|||���������������������������������������������������|\n|||and folate.|\n|||This grain is a great baby food as you can easily blend it and|\n|---|---|---|\n|||add it to other cereal dishes. It is a good source of vitamin A|\n|**Barley**||and folate.|\n|||This starchy vegetable is not on the top of the allergenic|\n|||foods, but it may cause some allergies. The American|\n|||Academy of Pediatrics Section on Allergy and Immunology|\n|||states:|\n|||“Most babies can start eating foods like corn after|\n|**Corn**||������������������������������������������|\n|||baby cereal, puréed meat, vegetables, or fruit)|\n|||without causing an allergic reaction”|\n|||Purée the corn using a food processor or blender to make it|\n|||safe for your baby to eat until he/she has teeth and can chew|\n|||the kernels completely.|\n**Sweet potatoes**\n|baby cereal, puréed meat, vegetables, or fruit)<br>without causing an allergic reaction”<br>Purée the corn using a food processor or blender to make it<br>safe for your baby to eat until he/she has teeth and can chew<br>the kernels completely.|baby cereal, puréed meat, vegetables, or fruit)<br>without causing an allergic reaction”<br>Purée the corn using a food processor or blender to make it<br>safe for your baby to eat until he/she has teeth and can chew<br>the kernels completely.|\n|---|---|\n|�������������������������������������������������||\n|They also contain an array of minerals including iron, calcium,||\n|selenium, and are a good source of most of the B vitamins as||\n|well as vitamin C.||\n|•|Steam or boil the potato until soft and tender (to test|\n||if it is ready to eat, gently stick a fork into the potato).|\n||If your baby can grasp a spoon and feed themselves,|\n||serve the potatoes mashed.  If not, serve chopped into<br>small pieces. Serve plain or with a pinch of thyme or any|\n||seasoning of choice.|\n|•|Sweet potatoes are also excellent when puréed. Use|\n||the same cooking method mentioned above, throw the|\n||potatoes into a blender, and add water depending on|\n||how thick you want the consistency to be.|",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_12": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **LEGUMES**\nLegumes represent an important food group, and their consumption should be encouraged daily as ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� and zinc, which makes them a good substitute for these animal foods. They are also an excellent ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� Legumes include but are not limited to chickpeas (hummus and nakhi), and fava beans (bajela and foul mudammes).",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_13": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **MILK, DAIRY PRODUCTS & ALTERNATIVES**\nHuman milk (or infant formula in certain situations) should be the only type of milk given to infants and young children. Cow’s milk as well as goat and camel milk should be avoided until 12 months of age, as young infants cannot digest it. The high concentration of protein and minerals in those milk types can stress your baby’s kidneys and cause anemia, fever, or diarrhea. You should also limit giving these ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� to your baby if recommended by the medical practitioner).\n�������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� cannot introduce other dairy products in your child’s diet. Hard cheeses, cottage cheese and yogurt can be given to your baby as a protein source but ensure to observe them closely for any reaction after introducing these foods.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_14": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **FISH, POULTRY, MEAT & ALTERNATIVES**\nFish, poultry, and meat are excellent sources of protein and essential minerals and should be introduced into your baby’s diet after six months of age. As your baby reaches six months of age, iron stores begin to decrease which is why iron and zinc found in protein-rich foods such as meat become crucial.\nIron and zinc are essential nutrients to combat the ��������������������������������������������������������� �������������������������������������������������� **Iron and** developmental behavior. Therefore, proper complementary **Zinc** feeding should include foods rich in iron and zinc to help support the production of red blood cells, to build a strong immunity and foster normal brain development.\n- �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� food before introducing a new one, to make sure that your baby did not develop any reaction to these ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������\n- ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ��������������������������������������������������������������������\n- Broil, boil, roast or bake these foods and limit frying and deep frying.\n- Thoroughly cook these foods to kill any bacteria.\n- Once cooked, cut up these foods and purée them to the desired consistency.\n- Use a separate blender for your baby’s foods, or make sure the blender is thoroughly cleaned before using it to prepare your baby’s foods.\n- As your baby’s feeding skills mature, you no longer need to purée these foods, you can start ���������������������������\n- ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� them).\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nMore on<br>Fish<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nFish is healthy for your child, and it is recommended that �������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������ ������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������ seafood (such as anchovies, Spanish mackerel (also known as ‘khanad” in Qatar) salmon, sardine, oysters, white ��������������������������������������������������������� ���������������������������������������������������������� ��������������������������������������������������������� �����������������������������������[ [28]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_15": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **EGGS**\nEggs are an excellent source of protein and are safe to introduce to your baby after six months of age. However, you must ensure they are cooked thoroughly. Although, egg allergies are common, it is not a reason to fear introducing this excellent source of protein into your baby’s diet. Just take special care to observe for any rashes or allergic reactions after its introduction.\nRaw or partially cooked eggs or foods that contain eggs, such as mayonnaise, icing, homemade ice cream, salad dressings etc., should NEVER be given to infants as they contain bacteria that may cause severe illness in your baby.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_16": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **BEVERAGES**\n**Water**\n**Fruit Juice**\nOnce you begin introducing complementary foods at six months of age, you can start giving your baby small amounts of water. Considering that the climate in Qatar can become quite hot, it would be a good idea to check with a doctor on how much water you should be giving your baby. Encourage your child to drink from a cup rather than a bottle, as this will promote the development of your child’s motor skills. This can start as early as six months of age.\nUnless otherwise advised by the doctor, infants less than 12 months of age should not be given juices since these may replace other, more nutritious foods. After your child is one year old or older, you can start giving them small amounts of fresh homemade juice or fresh 100% pasteurized fruit juice ���������������������������������������������������������� a bottle.\nIt is important to note that giving fruits (puréed or diced) to your baby instead of juices is always better since fruits are ��������������������������������������������������������������� ��������������������������������������������������������� reduce their appetite from eating nutritious whole foods. Giving your baby too much juice may also cause a diaper rash, diarrhea or unwanted weight gain because juices contain a lot of calories as compared to fresh fruits[[29-31]] .\nAre unpasteurized fruit juices safe for consumption? When ������������������������������������������������������ ������������������������������������������������������������ ������������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������� because it comes in more playful packaging. It is important, however, to ensure that the juice clearly states it is pasteurized, as unpasteurized juices may carry the bacteria E. coli which can make your baby very ill[ [32, 33]] .\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nSweetened<br>Beverages<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nHerbal<br>Teas and<br>�����������<br>Beverages<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nAny beverage with high sugar content, such as carbonated ������������������������������������������������������������������ recommended for children. Consumption of these types of beverages can cause tooth decay and may contribute to being overweight and obese.\nThe Gulf and Middle Eastern cultures rely heavily on the ������������������������������������������������������ ��������������������������������������������������������� believing that they would help with digestion and relaxation; ���������������������������������������������������������� allow the infant to speak at an early age. More research needs to be conducted on the safety of herbal teas and their impact on infants’ health and development. Thus, parents should consult a doctor before giving their baby any herbal tea.\n������������������������������������������������������� drinks or carbonated soft drinks) **should not** be given to ��������������������������������������������������������� your baby, leading to fussiness and disturbance of sleep. Similarly, tea and cocoa products contain a substance that is ���������������������������������������������������������� children.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n15 Oral Health<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nFeeding practices in infancy may increase the risk of early childhood caries, which are also known as baby bottle caries. Babies derive comfort from sucking on the bottle, and this may help them relax and fall asleep. However, you should not give a bottle of formula, juice or any other sweetened beverages to calm your baby or at bedtime since this will lead to teeth demineralization and, thus, tooth decay[[34, 35]] .\nThe American Academy of Pediatric Dentistry and the American Academy of Pediatrics have provided recommendations to prevent early childhood caries;[[30, 35]] :\n- Limit frequent consumption of liquids and solid foods that contain sugar. In particular, avoid ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ and sweetened milk to your baby.\n- �����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������\n- Your baby should be weaned from the bottle at 12-18 months of age.\n- At the age of 12 months, you should be taking your baby to see a dentist. Talk to the ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� emerges.\n- Use a gentle brush or a clean, soft cloth to wipe emerging baby teeth and promote good �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� right before bed.\n40\n**16 Supplements**\nAlways consult with the doctor before giving your baby any supplements. In most instances, a balanced and diverse diet will meet your child’s needs for the various nutrients. Thus, once your ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� the 6 food groups in order to meet their nutritional needs.\n- **Vitamin D:** This vitamin is crucial for healthy bones. The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends that all breastfed infants (whether exclusively or partially breastfed), and ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� take vitamin D supplements. When your baby starts complementary feeding, you can add the vitamin D drops to puréed food or porridge[[36]] .\n- **Iron:** ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� them meet iron requirements. Speak to the doctor about iron supplements and how long you should continue iron supplementation after your baby starts eating iron-containing �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� supplement[[36]] .\n- **Vitamin B12:** �������������������������������������������������������������������������� meat, eggs and dairy. Most children do not have any problem with this nutrient. However, for vegan moms who are breastfeeding their baby and who plan to introduce only plantbased foods into their child’s diet, there will be a need for vitamin B12 supplements. ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� formula, which is most often soy-based[[36]] .\n- **Other vitamins:** ������������������������������������������������������������������������ day should not be given any other vitamin supplements. This is because infant formula is ���������������������������[ [37]] .\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nAlways<br> IMPORTANT<br>consult the<br>NOTE<br>doctor before giving<br>your baby any<br>supplements.<br>41<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n17<br>Food Allergies<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nWhat is a food allergy?\nIt is an abnormal body response to a certain food or beverage[[38]] .\nHow can I reduce the risk of my child having a food allergy?\nYou cannot prevent your child from developing a certain food allergy, but studies have shown that following the below recommendations can prevent or delay food allergies in infants:\n- ��������������������������������������������������������\n- Do not begin complementary feeding before six months of age[[38]] (unless medically prescribed by your healthcare provider).\nAllergies to infant formula:\nBreastmilk is the best milk for your baby. If for any reason the baby is switched to cow’s milkbased infant formula, and you found out that the baby is allergic to it then consult the doctor or dietitian for advice on other options such as soy milk. If the infant was also found to be allergic to soy milk, then a special hypoallergenic formula is usually recommended.\nThere is no evidence that soy or goat-based formula will reduce the risk of developing allergic diseases in healthy infants.\nWhat are the most common allergens in the diet?\nWhen infants are introduced to complementary feeding, some may develop allergies to certain foods. Around 90% of all food allergies are caused by the following types of foods[ [38, 39]] :\n- Animal-based milk such as cow’s milk\n- Eggs\n- Peanuts\n- Soy\n- Tree nuts\n- Fish\n- �����������������������������������\n- Wheat\n- Seeds\nWhen introducing foods to the baby, especially those foods that are known to cause allergic reactions (as listed above), make sure to introduce each type of food, one at a time, and in small amounts, so you will be able to notice any reactions or symptoms in your baby[[39]] . Do not be scared to introduce these types of foods to your child. In fact, there is no need to limit any of ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� diet[[39]] .\nSome individuals can have allergies for food additives including colors and preservatives, but allergic reactions from ordinary food items are usually more common[ [39]] .\nWhat are the symptoms of food allergies?\nAn allergic reaction can begin within minutes to an hour after ingesting the food or beverage that �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� more symptoms. The most common symptoms of food allergy are[ [38]] :\n- Diarrhea\n- Vomiting\n- Cough\n- Swelling\n- Dry and itchy skin (Eczema)\n- Itching or swelling of the lips, tongue, or mouth\n- Itching or tightness in the throat\n- Skin rashes\n- Sore, red and/or itchy eyes\n- Runny or blocked nose\n- Lowered blood pressure\n- Stomach cramps and pain\n- Red itchy bumps on the skin (Hives)\n- Trouble breathing or shortness of breath\n- Wheezing (coarse sound when breathing)\nIn some cases, severe allergic reaction may occur, known as “anaphylaxis”; this can be lifethreating[[39, 40]] ������������������������������������������������������������������������������� �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������[ [38]] . Take care when introducing new foods and closely observe whether your child develops any allergic reaction to a newly introduced food.\nHow do we diagnose a food allergy?\nA diagnosis should be done by a doctor. You should not make the diagnosis yourself to limit any unnecessary dietary restrictions. In case a food allergy is diagnosed, you must have a dietary plan to replace the eliminated food items, and you also need to have a plan in case of emergency [41]. If your infant/child develops any of the typical allergy-related symptoms after eating any type of food or beverage, you should immediately contact the doctor.\nNutritional concerns in infants and children with food allergies\n������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ Therefore, it is important to keep in mind that eliminating a certain food group (because of �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� growth problems in your child[ [42]] .\nFor example, milk, eggs and soy are good sources of fat and protein. Eliminating these food items �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� are not replaced by other good sources[ [42]] .\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� certain vitamins, which can lead to poor growth.\n- Diets that are low in protein may also lead to protein malnutrition and hence poor growth[[42]] .\nAnother example is wheat. This cereal provides the body with carbohydrates, which are known to be an important source of energy for your child’s body, and particularly the brain. Wheat also contains important vitamins and minerals. So if the child is allergic to wheat, other alternative �����������������������������������������������������������������������������[[42]] .\nAnother potential challenge is that children that have one or more food allergies might experience some dietary behavior problems more than other children. For example, they may develop “food aversion” (i.e., refusing certain types of food) or a state of anxiety about food, which again can lead to inadequate food intake[ [42]] .\nThis is why it is very important that the doctor monitors the growth of infants and children with food allergies[[42]] . It is also important that the doctor or dietitian provide the right alternatives to �����������������������������������������������������������������[[42]] .  The doctor may sometimes prescribe supplements when needed[[42]] .\nWhat should I do if my child was diagnosed with a food allergy?\n������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ food or beverage that causes the allergic reaction[ [38, 40, 41, 43]] . It is therefore important to get the help of a dietitian to plan an adequate, healthy and balanced diet for your child, to avoid any �������������������������������������������������������������������������������[[43]] . Below are some practical tips that can help you in managing your child’s food allergy:\n- Check with your dietitian and doctor to  identify food alternatives or nutritional supplements ���������������������[[38]] .\n- �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� item[[41]] .\n- Educate your family (at home) and teachers (in the nursery) about your child’s allergies and what to do in case of an emergency[ [41]] .\n- If the doctor has prescribed any medications in case of an allergic reaction, always keep those medications at hand[ [38]] .\n- ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������� complications caused by food allergies[ [40]] .\n������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ after a certain amount of time to evaluate whether the child has outgrown the allergy. Some allergies may in fact be outgrown with time, and the foods may end up being tolerated after reaching the age of three or four years old. This must be done under the doctor’s supervision[ [38]] .\nTips when dining out of the house:\nAs a parent of a child with one or more food allergies, eating out of the house can be challenging. The following tips can help you:\n- Check the menu online before going to the restaurant.\n- Read and/or ask about the ingredients before ordering any dish.\n- Let the server be aware of your child’s allergy and ensure there is no cross-contamination when preparing your child’s dish.\n- ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� �������������������������������������������������\n- ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� dishes[[38]] .\nFood allergy card:\nHaving a food allergy card can help your child and especially help the people around them (if you ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� child at all times, including at the nursery, when the child is visiting a friend, at a party and/or in a restaurant. Inform any adult in charge that the child has this card, such as the teacher at the nursery or the parents of the friend that your child is visiting [38].\nThe food allergy card should contain the following information:\n- The name of the child\n- Food items your child is allergic to\n- What to do in case of emergency\n- Parent’s name and phone number\nThis card can be easily done at home (below is the card template).\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nFOOD ALLERGY CARD<br>My name is  .....................................................................................................................................................................<br>I am allergic to  ..........................................................................................................................................................<br>.....................................................................................................................................................................................................<br>.....................................................................................................................................................................................................<br>I cannot eat food containing .......................................................................................................................<br>.....................................................................................................................................................................................................<br>.....................................................................................................................................................................................................<br>even in small amounts, so please avoid any form of cross-contamination.<br>In case of emergency, please call 999 and notify my parents.<br>My parents contact number: ...................................................<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n18<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_72_1_17": "### **Hunger cues**\n#### **Food Safety Considerations**\nComplementary feeding (i.e., solid and soft foods) should be introduced at six months of age. Babies have a higher risk of food poisoning due to their immature immune systems. Therefore, it urc sig ecitcarp ot laicooh dyeigna enorp dpof reoh dannilda ot gva dionof fo sesac yop dsioonin .g Keep these simple vital tips in mind to ensure that you and your baby will have a fruitful experience when introducing solid and soft foods[[4]] .\n- Always wash your hands thoroughly before preparing the food and before feeding your baby.\n- Always wash your baby’s hands before feeding as they will uncontrollably want to feed themselves.\n- Always use clean utensils and surfaces when preparing food and when feeding your baby.\n- Always ensure that food is cooked thoroughly.\n- Always store food safely in airtight containers and appropriate temperatures.\nBy paying close attention to hygienic practices, you can lower the incidence of gastrointestinal illnesses such as diarrhea. Refer to Appendix 2.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n19<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_73_0_0": "## **Physical Activity Recommendations for Infants and Young Children**\nIt is important for the development of your child to have some form of physical activity. This can be achieved in various ways:",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_73_1_0": "## **Physical Activity Recommendations for Infants and Young Children**\n### **For infants (<12 months)[ [44, 45]] :**\nAn exercise regimen for infants is impractical: infants do not follow instructions. However, it is crucial to facilitate some form of physical activity daily.\nInteract often with your baby and provide opportunities for “tummy time”.\n- Tummy time is when you place your baby on their stomach while they are awake, and only when supervised.\n- Tummy time can help develop strength in your baby’s neck, arms and back.\n- You can start your baby’s tummy time “training” as soon as you leave the hospital. During ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� 10-15 minutes per day. As your baby grows and gains strength you should extend the time gradually.\n- Initiate tummy time when your baby is energetic following a nap or a diaper change.\n- Create a safe environment such as a playmat or clean towel. You might want to add some toys to stimulate your baby’s attention.\n- Once your baby starts enjoying this position gradually increase the session frequency and duration throughout the day. If your baby is not able to crawl yet, aim for a minimum of 30 minutes per day in several “tummy time” sessions.\n- As good as tummy time is for your baby, never put your baby to sleep on their stomach. ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� (SIDS).\nFor a healthy development, avoid “locking up” your child in prams, strollers, or highchairs for more than 60 minutes. Your baby develops daily and needs to start exploring their surroundings. Make sure to allow some opportunities for:\n- Floor-based play.\n- Reaching out and grabbing objects.\n- Crawling.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_73_1_1": "### **For infants (<12 months)[ [44, 45]] :**\n#### **For toddlers (1-2 years)[[44-46]] :**\nToddlers this age should engage in at least 3 hours of physical activity throughout the day (not all at once). This should be achieved through fun activities that promote exploration and discovery. Below are some tips for you and your toddler:\n- Include a wider variety of physical activity options through active play (e.g., standing, rolling, playing, and moving around).\n- When the child starts walking, encourage them to walk more, and move around the house.\n- When the child can balance well, encourage them to take part in activities such as running, jumping, climbing, swimming, bouncing, catching, kicking, ball games etc.\n- **�������������������������������������������������������[ [44, 45] ]**\nPhysical activity helps infants and toddlers to:\n- Develop locomotor and movement skills\n- Develop strong bones and muscles\n- Maintain a healthy weight\n- Improve social and intellectual skills\n- Adopting physical activity as a habit early in life",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_74_0_0": "## **Safety tips[[44]] :**\n- Activities should be based on physical maturity rather than chronological age to reduce the risk of injury, because each child grows at their own pace.\n- Frequency, intensity, and time should gradually progress as the child develops.\n- Supervise your child to prevent at home-accidents.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_74_1_0": "## **Safety tips[[44]] :**\n### **Limiting sedentary behavior (sitting)[[44, 45]] :**\nReducing sedentary behavior (sitting or restrained) during your child’s waking hours is recommended to support healthy growth and development.\n- Do not allow any screen time for children under the age of two years.\n- Do not restrain your child for more than one hour at a time (i.e., in a highchair or stroller).\n- Integrate active fun activities in the child’s everyday routines.\n- Keep electronic equipment out of sight.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_75_0_0": "## **APPENDIX 1:**\nCHILD’S DAILY RECOMMENDATIONS FROM THE DIFFERENT FOOD GROUPS\n- ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������[ [47]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_75_1_0": "## **APPENDIX 1:**\n### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n���������������������������������������������������\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nVEGETABLES FRUITS<br>1 Portion 1 Portion<br>1-3 Cherry Tomatoes  ½ - 2 Tablespoons 2-6 Carrot Sticks 3-10 strawberries 1-3 dates    ¼-½ medium apple<br>of Cooked Spinach<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_75_1_1": "### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n#### **Examples of one portion of vegetable:**\n- 2-6 carrot sticks\n- 1-3 cherry tomatoes\n- �������������������������������������������������������������������������������\n- ½-2 tablespoons of roasted vegetables\n- ½-1 small bowl of homemade vegetable soup",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_75_1_2": "### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n#### **Examples of one portion of fruit:**\n- ¼-½ medium apple, orange, pear, mango, or peach\n- ¼-1 medium banana\n- ½-1 clementine, apricot, plum\n- 3-10 strawberries, raspberries, blueberries, grapes (halved)\n- 1-3 dates\n- ������������������������",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_75_1_3": "### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n#### **CEREALS AND STARCHY VEGETABLES**\n�������������������������������������������������������������������������������� General recommendations are 5 portions per day\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nCEREALS AND STARCHY VEGETABLES<br>1 Portion<br>2-5 tablespoons ½-1 bread slice 3-6 tablespoons ¼-½ baked potato<br>cooked rice breakfast cereals<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_75_1_4": "### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n#### **Examples of one portion:**\n- 2-5 tablespoons of cooked rice or pasta\n- 2-4 tablespoons of couscous\n- ½-1 bread slice, chapatti bread\n- ¼-½ pita bread\n- 3-6 tablespoons of breakfast cereals\n- ¼-½ baked potato, medium-sized; ½-1 ½ egg-sized boiled potatoes",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_75_1_5": "### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n#### **Practical tips:**\n- Add cereals and starchy vegetables to each meal.\n- ������������������������������������������������\n- Keep biscuits, cakes, pastries, and pies for special occasions.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_75_1_6": "### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n#### **LEGUMES**\nEat legumes daily. Legumes are counted as a protein rich food.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nLENTILS BEANS CHICKPEAS  RAW NUTS<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nMaintain a daily consumption of protein foods, including legumes, unsalted, raw nuts and �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� details on the number of portions and portion sizes.\n- �������������������\n- Include foods rich in vitamin C to enhance absorption of iron and zinc from legumes.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_76_0_0": "## **MILK, DAIRY PRODUCTS AND ALTERNATIVES**\nMaintain a daily consumption of milk and dairy products General recommendations are 3 portions per day\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nMILK, DAIRY PRODUCTS AND ALTERNATIVES<br>1 Portion<br>100-120 mL 3 tablespoons 2-4 tablespoons 2-4 tablespoons<br>milk plain yogurt  grated cheese rice pudding<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_76_1_0": "## **MILK, DAIRY PRODUCTS AND ALTERNATIVES**\n### **Examples of one portion:**\n- 100-120 mL of milk\n- 3 tablespoons of plain yogurt or 125 mL of laban\n- 1 cheese ball or 2-4 tablespoons of grated cheese\n- 2-4 tablespoons of rice pudding",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_76_1_1": "### **Examples of one portion:**\n#### **FISH, POULTRY, MEAT AND ALTERNATIVES**\nThese foods are rich sources of protein.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nFISH POULTRY AND MEAT EGGS NUTS AND SEEDS<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nMaintain a daily consumption of protein foods, including legumes, nuts and seeds and/or ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� number of portions and portion sizes.\n- Fish, poultry, meat, eggs, unsalted, raw nuts and seeds, and legumes are good sources of protein.\n- �������������������������������������������\n- ��������������������������������������������������������\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nBox 1:  Protein Foods<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n**Make sure to include protein rich foods in your child’s daily diet. These include legumes, �������������������������������������������������������������������**\nGeneral recommendations for protein foods are 2 portions per day.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_76_1_2": "### **Examples of one portion:**\n#### **Examples of one portion include:**\n- 2-4 tablespoons of cooked beans, chickpeas or lentils\n- 15-30 g of seafood, skinless chicken, and lean meats\n- ½-1 ½  tablespoon of canned sardines\n- ½-1 ½ tablespoon of canned tuna (in water not oil)\n- ½-1 boiled egg\n- 1-2 tablespoons of chopped or ground unsalted, raw nuts or seeds\n- 1-2 tablespoons of hummus\n- 1 tablespoon of peanut butter\nThe number of portions of protein per day increases with the child’s age: 2 portions/day for toddlers aged 1-2 years; 2-5 portions for children aged 2-5 years.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_76_1_3": "### **Examples of one portion:**\n#### **APPENDIX 2:**\nGENERAL FOOD SAFETY CONSIDERATIONS\nEating food contaminated with certain bacteria, viruses, parasites or contains harmful toxins can cause foodborne illnesses. These illnesses are usually acute, occurring within 1 to 36 hours after consuming the contaminated or poisonous food. The symptoms typically last from 1 to 7 days and include one or more of the following symptoms: abdominal pain, diarrhea, vomiting, feeling sick, dehydration and collapsing. Foods that are most likely to contain harmful bacteria or viruses fall into two categories:\n1. Uncooked fresh vegetables and fruits\n2. Some animal products, such as unpasteurized (raw) milk; soft cheeses made with raw milk; ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� juices; luncheon meats and deli-type salads (without added preservatives)\nWhile most children who develop a foodborne illness will get better without medical interventions, it is advisable to consult with the doctor if symptoms are severe or persist for more than a week.\nPreparing and consuming safe foods starts at the time of food purchase. Box 1 outlines a few tips to assist you in shopping for safe food for your children.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_76_1_4": "### **Examples of one portion:**\n#### Box 1. Tips for safe food purchase\n- Purchase food from reliable sources.\n- Read the “Product Label” for food safety information on all foods and beverages.\n- Put raw seafood, poultry, or meat in separate plastic bags.\n- Pick up perishable foods last, and plan to go directly home from the grocery store.\n- Buy only pasteurized milk, soft cheeses made with pasteurized milk, and pasteurized juices that have been treated to control harmful bacteria.\n- Always purchase refrigerated eggs.\n- Do not buy food displayed in unsafe or unclean conditions.\n- Always check the expiry date of the food to be purchased:\n- A “Sell-By” or “Expiry (EXP)” date tells the store how long to display the product for sale. You should buy the product before the date expires.\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� not a purchase or safety date.\n- A “Use-By” date is the last date recommended for product use while at peak quality. The date has been determined by the manufacturer of the product.\n����������������������������������������������������������������������������� ensure proper handling and consumption. These practices fall under the following four categories: **Clean, Separate, Cook and Chill** . More details about these practices are outlined in Box 2[ [48]] . Box 2. Tips for proper food handling **Clean:** • Wash your hands before, during, and after food preparation and consumption. • Wash your hands with soap for at least 60 seconds. • Practice good personal hygiene during food handling and preparation activities. • ����������������������������������������������������������������������������� tabletops, cooking surfaces and the sink with hot, soapy water before you cook and after they come into contact with raw seafood, poultry, meat, eggs �������� • ����������������������������������������������������������������������������� Vinegar may also be used to disinfect vegetables and fruits. • Limit washing eggs, raw meat and poultry since washing causes bacteria to spread faster. Instead, pat the eggs with a clean, damp towel and the raw meat and poultry with a separate damp towel as well. • Wipe food packaging with soap and water before opening, especially the lids of cans and jars.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n|||\n|---|---|\n|Separate:|• Keep cooked and ready-to-eat foods away from raw seafood, poultry,|\n|meat, and eggs in the refrigerator while cooking. Juices from raw seafood,|\n|poultry, meats and cracked eggs can contaminate ready-to-eat foods, so it is|\n|important to separate them.|\n|• Ensure that cooked and ready-to-eat foods are placed on top shelves, while|\n|raw foods are placed on lower shelves in the refrigerator in order to prevent|\n|the transfer of bacteria from raw foods to cooked foods.|\n|• If possible, use separate sets of knives, cutting boards, and utensils for|\n|seafood, poultry, meat, and eggs. Ensure to wash them in hot, soapy water or|\n|in the dishwasher between uses.|\n|• Plates that touch raw foods are not safe to reuse for cooked foods until they|\n|have been washed. Use clean plates to hold cooked foods, and wash plates|\n|thoroughly in hot, soapy water after they touch raw foods.|\n|56|\n**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n- **Cook:** • Use clean water.\n- Cook all food thoroughly:\n- The cooking temperature needs to reach at least 75º C or above to ensure the food is safe and free from all pathogenic bacteria.\n- A food thermometer must be used to measure the internal temperature of cooked foods. Check the internal temperature in several places to make sure that the seafood, poultry, meat, or egg product is cooked to safe minimum internal temperatures.\n- For microwave or oven cooking: always cover food, stir, and rotate for even cooking.\n- Consume leftovers within 3-4 days.\n- Reheat leftovers only once. If leftovers are not consumed after being reheated, throw them out.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_76_1_5": "### **Examples of one portion:**\n#### **Chill:**\n- ���������������������������������������������������������������������� �������������������������������������������������������������������������� bacteria.\n- Do not keep food at room temperature for more than 2 hours.\nThere are a few general guidelines that will help reduce the risk of foodborne illnesses:\n- Protect food from insects, rodents, and other animals.\n- Store non-perishable food products in a cool and dry place.\n- ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� fruit juice.\n- You cannot tell by looking, smelling, or even tasting a food whether it contains pathogens. Yet these pathogens-like disease causing bacteria, viruses, or parasites, can make you sick.\n- You should never taste food to determine if it is safe to eat.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_76_1_6": "### **Examples of one portion:**\n#### **REFERENCES**\n1. Ministry of Health. Qatar Dietary Guidelines; Health Promotion and Non-communicable Diseases Section, Public Health Department: Doha, Qatar, 2015; Available online: https:// www.fao.org/3/az908e/az908e.pdf.\n2. World Health Organization. Health topics: complementary feeding. Available online: https://www.who.int/health-topics/complementary-feeding#tab=tab_1 (accessed on 22 March 2022).\n3. Martorell, R.; Khan, L. K.; Schroeder, D. G. Reversibility of stunting: epidemiological ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������\n4. Pan American Health Organization; World Health Organization. Guiding Principles for Complementary Feeding of the Breastfed Child; Division of Health Promotion and Protection Food and Nutrition Program: Washington DC, 2003; Available online: https:// www.who.int/nutrition/publications/guiding_principles_compfeeding_breastfed.pdf.\n5. World Health Organization. The WHO child growth standards. Available online: https:// www.who.int/tools/child-growth-standards/standards (accessed on 20 March 2022).\n6. World Health Organization. Training course on child growth assessment. WHO child growth standards: Interpreting growth indicators; World Health Organization: Geneva, Switzerland, 2008; Available online: https://www.who.int/childgrowth/training/module_c_ interpreting_indicators.pdf?ua=1.\n7. Canadian Paediatric Society. A health professional’s guide for using the new WHO growth charts. Paediatr Child Health 2010, 15, 84-98.\n8. World Health Organization. Infant and young child feeding. Available online: https://www. who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/infant-and-young-child-feeding (accessed on 22 March 2021).\n9. ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ and measurement methods. Available online: https://www.who.int/publications/i/ item/9789240018389 (accessed on 22 March 2022).\n10