  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_77_1_0": "## TABLE OF\n### **CONTENTS**\n|Assessment of Child’s Weight and Height|Assessment of Child’s Weight and Height|Assessment of Child’s Weight and Height||5|\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n|Dietary Recommendations||||7|\n|Fluid Intake Recommendations||||10|\n|How to Boost my Child’s Immunity||||11|\n|Picky Eating||||12|\n|Force-Feeding||||71|\n|Vegetarian Children||||18|\n|Tips|for A Healthy and Safe Lunchbox|||19|\n|Food Safety Considerations||||21|\n|Food Allergies||||22|\n|Oral|Health|||27|\n|||||28|\n|Physical Activity Recommendations for Toddlers and Preschoolers||||29|\n|Importance of Adequate Sleep||||30|\n|Appendix 1:|||||\n|Children's daily recommendations from the diferent food groups||||31|\n|Appendix 2:|||||\n|General Food Safety Considerations||||35|\n|References|||||\n|||||39|\nHealthy diets are important at every age. This chapter focuses on toddlers aged 2-3 years and preschoolers aged 3-5 years. Toddlers and preschoolers are very receptive and impressionable, which gives you the perfect opportunity to help them establish healthy eating habits. Although toddlers and preschoolers have a slower growth compared to infants, they still need enough energy to fuel their active play and enough nutrients to support their growth and development.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n01<br>Assessment of Child’s Weight and Height<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nIt is important that a doctor or healthcare provider monitors the growth of your child by measuring his/her weight, height, and head circumference (for children under 24-36 months). The doctor will later draw these measurements on the appropriate growth charts in order to assess your child’s growth and development.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_77_1_1": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### **What are growth charts?**\n- Growth charts are graphic presentations that illustrate the distribution of body measurements in children (weight, height, head circumference, body mass index (BMI)).\n- Growth charts are the most useful tool for assessing growth and nutritional status in children.\n- The use of the appropriate growth charts may identify abnormal trends in growth that can be indicative of poor nutrition or the presence of disease.\nIn some instances, the measurements may reveal certain growth-related problems, such as:\n- The child has a low weight for his/her age (underweight or severely underweight): This may be the result of the child being too thin or too short for his/her age. It may be the result of poor nutrition or certain illnesses. Underweight children are more vulnerable to diseases and may experience delays in their development.\n- The child is short for his/her age (stunted or severely stunted): If your child’s height is below the normal range for his/her age (a condition referred to as stunting), this may be the result of long-term malnutrition or illness. It has consequences on the physical development of the child and is often accompanied by poor mental development.\n- The child has lost weight (wasted or severely wasted): This may occur because of poor nutrition or illness. Wasted children have a higher risk of contracting diseases and illnesses.\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� genetic factors (i.e., running in the family), or a combination of all these factors. In rare cases, obesity in children may result from a medical condition, which is diagnosed by the doctor. Overweight and obesity early in life can increase the risk of obesity and chronic diseases later in life.\n- The child has a larger-than-normal or smaller-than-normal head circumference: This helps in assessing brain size as an indicator of possible developmental or nutritional problems.\nBox 1 below summarizes the health and social implications associated with overweight and obesity, as well as those associated with the child being underweight, wasted, or stunted[ [1, 2]] .\nBox 1. Implications associated with overweight and obesity, as well as those associated with underweight, wasting, and stunting among 2–5-year-old children\n**Overweight and obesity**\n- Social problems including bullying\n- ���������������������������������������������������\n- Lower quality of life\n- Type 2 diabetes, high blood pressure, high blood cholesterol, and cardiovascular diseases later in life\n- Joints and bone problems\n**Underweight, wasting, and stunting**\n- Social problems including bullying\n- Delayed mental growth and reduced intellectual capacity\n- Poor school performance\n- Increased risk of infections and illness\n- �����������������������������������������������\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n02<br>Dietary Recommendations<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n�������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� and unhealthy fats[[3]] .\n�������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� diet to your child[[4]] ��������������������� **Appendix 1** for the number of servings from each food group per day.\nTable 1. Practical tips on how to achieve an adequate and balanced diet\n|Food groups<br>What to include<br>Practical tips<br>Vegetables<br>All fresh, frozen, and<br>dried vegetables<br>•<br>Make vegetables part of your child’s daily meals<br>•<br>��������������������������������������<br>sticks or cucumber slices, cherry tomatoes, among<br>others<br>•<br>Choose a variety of colorful vegetables to provide<br>����������������������������������������<br>•<br>Favor fresh or frozen vegetables over canned<br>vegetables, since the canned varieties contain a<br>lot of salt|Food groups|What to include|Practical tips|\n|---|---|---|---|\n||Fruits|All fresh, frozen,<br>canned, and dried<br>fruits|•<br>Favor whole fruits instead of fruit juices (if juice is<br>������������������������������������������<br>ensure the quantity does not exceed ½ cup which<br>is 125 mL)<br>•<br>����������������������������������������<br>or at home<br>•<br>Choose a variety of colorful fruits to provide your<br>������������������������������������|\n|Cereals<br>and starchy<br>vegetables<br>Bread, rice, oats,<br>pasta, couscous,<br>bulgur, wheat,<br>potatoes, sweet<br>potato, corn,<br>balaleet, jareesh<br>(crushed wheat),<br>harees, freeka<br>•<br>Add cereals to each meal<br>•<br>Choose whole grain cereals (such as whole wheat<br>bread, brown rice, whole wheat pasta) instead of<br>��������������<br>•<br>Keep biscuits, cakes, pastries, and pies for special<br>occasions<br>Legumes<br>Beans, lentils,<br>chickpeas, foul<br>muddammes,<br>hummus, bajela<br>(fava beans), nakhi<br>(chickpeas)<br>•<br>Add legumes to your child’s diet daily<br>•<br>Include foods rich in vitamin C to enhance<br>absorption of iron and zinc from legumes<br>Milk, Dairy<br>Products and<br>Alternatives<br>Milk, cheese, yogurt,<br>laban, labneh, or<br>������������������<br>beverages<br>•<br>Encourage your child to consume milk rather than<br>sugar-sweetened beverages (such as carbonated<br>soft drinks)<br>•<br>�������������������������������������<br>crackers topped with white cheese, as one of their<br>snacks|Cereals<br>and starchy<br>vegetables|Bread, rice, oats,<br>pasta, couscous,<br>bulgur, wheat,<br>potatoes, sweet<br>potato, corn,<br>balaleet, jareesh<br>(crushed wheat),<br>harees, freeka|•<br>Add cereals to each meal<br>•<br>Choose whole grain cereals (such as whole wheat<br>bread, brown rice, whole wheat pasta) instead of<br>��������������<br>•<br>Keep biscuits, cakes, pastries, and pies for special<br>occasions|\n|---|---|---|---|\n|8<br>Fish, poultry,<br>meat, and<br>alternatives<br>������������������<br>poultry and meat<br>Alternatives:<br>Unsalted, raw nuts<br>and seeds; legumes<br>**Fish:**<br>•<br>����������������������������������<br>•<br>����������������������������������<br>(“khanad”), sardines, and salmon<br>**Poultry and meat:**<br>•<br>Choose skinless poultry and lean cuts of meat<br>(lean ground beef)<br>•<br>Limit processed meats (hot dogs, pepperoni,<br>salami) and smoked meats<br>**Nuts and seeds:**<br>•<br>Choose unsalted, raw nuts and seeds as part of a<br>healthy snack|Fish, poultry,<br>meat, and<br>alternatives|������������������<br>poultry and meat<br>Alternatives:<br>Unsalted, raw nuts<br>and seeds; legumes|**Fish:**<br>•<br>����������������������������������<br>•<br>����������������������������������<br>(“khanad”), sardines, and salmon<br>**Poultry and meat:**<br>•<br>Choose skinless poultry and lean cuts of meat<br>(lean ground beef)<br>•<br>Limit processed meats (hot dogs, pepperoni,<br>salami) and smoked meats<br>**Nuts and seeds:**<br>•<br>Choose unsalted, raw nuts and seeds as part of a<br>healthy snack|\n|||||",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_77_1_2": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### **PROTEIN FOODS**\n����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� poultry lean meat, and eggs, as well as unsalted, raw nuts and seeds\n�������������������������������������������������������������������������������� �������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������������������������ �������������������������������������������������������������������������� More on Fish ��������������������������������������������������������������������������� ��������������������������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������������������������������ ����������������������������������������������[[5]] .\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nIMPORTANT<br>NOTE<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nChildren do not need to eat chocolate or sweets to feel energetic! They can get all the energy they need from a healthy and varied diet that includes the six food groups (refer to Appendix 1)\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n03 Fluid Intake Recommendations<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ recommendations according to your child’s age[ [6]] :\n- **2–3-year-old:** 4 cups (1 L) from water (and other beverages).\n- **4–5-year-old:** 5 cups (1.25 L) from water (and other beverages).\n- 1 cup = 250 mL\nIf you were told by a doctor that your child is underweight or obese, then make sure to consult �������������������������������������������������������������������������������\nWhen choosing beverages other than water, be aware that:\n- Sugar-sweetened beverages such as carbonated soft drinks and fruit drinks should be limited. These are high in added sugars, which can contribute to tooth decay and weight gain, while also replacing other more nutritious beverages such as milk.\n- Fruits are rich in natural sugars. Hence, fresh fruit juices are high in nutrients but are also ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� maximum of one serving (125 mL- half a cup) of fresh fruit juice (with no added sugar) to your child per day.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n04<br>How to Boost My Child’s Immunity<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nChildren need adequate intakes of nutrients and vitamins to help boost their immune system and protect them against infections. However, there are no magical foods or supplements that will boost your child’s immune system[[7]] . The best advice for supporting your child’s immunity is ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� diet that is varied and balanced which consists of food and beverages from the six food groups. Prioritize foods that are nutrient-rich such as vegetables and fruits which supply an abundant amount of antioxidants, vitamins, and minerals. Make sure to also limit their consumption of processed foods, snacks and foods that are high in sugar, salt, and unhealthy fats. Review Appendix 1 for details pertinent to dietary recommendations for your child.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_77_1_3": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### **05 Picky Eating**\nMany children go through a phase of refusing certain food types, especially when trying new foods. These children are known as “picky eaters”. This behavior tends to occur especially in ����������������������������������������������������������������������������[[8, 9]] . It is the child’s way of showing you their independence; it is also considered a normal phase of growing up. If ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� stressful. But you need to know that picky eating rarely causes any serious nutritional, medical or growth problems for the child, and it is a phase that most children grow out of it[[8]] .\n�������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� eaters.” In these cases, professionals may consider this as a feeding disorder, and you will need the help of a health professional to help your child grow out of it. The section below explains the �������������������������������������������������������[ [8]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_77_1_4": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### **Picky eaters & Extreme picky eaters**\nExtreme picky eating can last for a longer time as compared to picky eating. Extreme picky eaters can grow out of it over months or years; however, this usually needs to be done with the help of a health professional[[8]] . Extreme picky eating is usually more common in children with social communication disorders[[8]] .\nAlthough being a picky eater usually is harmless, being an extreme picky eater can cause serious ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������[[8]] . Table 2 provides you with a direct comparison between the two behaviors.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n12<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nTable 2. Comparison between picky eating and extreme picky eating characteristics in children ����������������������\n|**Picky eating**<br>**Extreme picky eating**|**Picky eating**<br>**Extreme picky eating**|\n|---|---|\n|• Very common in children.<br>• ��������������������������<br>years.<br>How common is it?<br>• Less common.<br>• More common in children with<br>social communication disorders.||\n|• No health/growth consequences or<br>only minor ones.<br>Health/Growth<br>consequences<br>• Moderate to severe health/growth<br>consequences.<br>• But, in some cases, there is no<br>health/growth consequences or<br>only minor ones.||\n|• Can be very stressful for parents.<br>Impact on parents<br>• Usually very stressful for parents.||\n|• Usually, children grow out of<br>it within a period of weeks to<br>months.<br>Do children grow out<br>of it?<br>• Can take a longer time (months or<br>years) for children to grow out of it.<br>• Management requires the help of a<br>health professional.||\n|• They eat a range of food items,<br>with a preference for some food<br>items from each food group.<br>• On some days, they may only eat<br>very little amounts, or they may<br>��������������������������<br>narrow range of food types.<br>Eating habits<br>• They eat a limited range of food<br>�������������������������������<br>types.<br>• They often exclude some food<br>groups altogether.||\n|• Picky eaters are upset when new<br>food items are introduced and their<br>������������������������<br>Feelings towards new<br>food items<br>• Extreme picky eaters are upset<br>when new food items are introduced<br>and when their favorite food is not<br>�����������������������������<br>can be more extreme.||\n|• ����������������������<br>refused food item in other foods<br>that the child likes.<br>Hiding food in other<br>food items<br>• �������������������������<br>because the child can detect it.||\n|Hiding food in other<br>food items||\n|������������������<br>food if hungry?|• They would eventually eat the<br>����������������������������<br>themselves.<br>• ���������������������������<br>usually, and they may be at risk of<br>being ill from starving themselves[8].|\n||13|",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_77_1_5": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### **When to seek professional help?**\nDo not get frustrated if your child is a picky eater. Just provide your child with healthy food choices and try your best to help your child grow out of this phase. In fact, most picky eaters remain healthy, and their eating habits tend to improve gradually as they get older[[10]] . If your ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� this problem[[8]] .\nBox 2 provides you with some useful steps to follow if your child is a picky eater[[8]] .\n|Box 2. Steps to follow with your “picky eater” child|Box 2. Steps to follow with your “picky eater” child|Box 2. Steps to follow with your “picky eater” child|\n|---|---|---|\n|**Establish**||• ����������������������������������������������������������|\n|**a clear**||them eat something nutritious every 2-3 hours).|\n|**eating**||• ��������������������������������������������������������|\n|**routine**||child’s appetite.|\n|||• Mealtime should be around 20-30 minutes. Do not rush your child|\n|||while they are eating.|\n|||• ���������������������������������������������������������|\n|||place.|\n|||• Involve the child in the routine. For example, after washing their|\n|||hands, they can help you in setting the table and at the end of the|\n|||meal they can help you in clearing it.|\n|**Limit**<br>**beverage**||• ��������������������������������������������������������<br>at the end of the meal/snack.|\n|**consump-**<br>**tion at**||• �������������������������������������������������������|\n|**mealtime**||eat less amounts.|\n|**Encourage**||• Eat together as a family as often as you can. Be a role model and eat|\n|**a healthy**||with your child because children usually imitate their parents.|\n|**attitude**||• Let your child enjoy eating with other children.|\n|**towards**<br>**eating**||• ��������������������������������������������������������<br>This can encourage them to try it.|\n|||• Encourage your child to eat but never force them to eat.|\n|||• Let your child learn to eat while listening to their appetite; do not|\n|||force them to eat more than they can or to clear their plates.|\n|||• Try to always have a calm and relaxed  environment when eating.|\n|||• ����������������������������������������������������������������|\n|||• Try to avoid anything that can distract the child from eating such as|\n|||television, electronic devices and toys. The child’s attention should be|\n|||focused on the eating experience.|\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������������� ����������������������������������������������������������������������� ���������������������������������������������������������������� than 10 times before the child accepts it.\n- Divide eXach main meal into two courses: a savory main course and a healthy dessert. Examples of a healthy dessert include a fresh whole fruit, fruit salad, or a yogurt.\n- Do not use desserts as a reward for eating other foods; this approach will make desserts more exciting for them and, as a result, may impact their acceptance of other foods.\n- Let your child be a part of purchasing the food, preparing it, and plating it.\n- Encourage good behavior at mealtime by rewarding the child with “non-food” items.\n- Verbal praise or a loving look are considered positive in developing food preferences.\n**Decide what �������� your child**\n- ���������������������������������������������������������������� ��������������������������������������\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������� possible. But make sure that it is suitable for the child’s age (such as mashed, chopped, etc.).\n- Try adding some herbs and spices to make the food tastier for the child.\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������� ����������������������������������������������\n- �������������������������������������������������������������\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������ appropriate to their needs.\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������ maximum of 2 kinds and ask them to choose their preference.\n- Try to mix the new food item with a food that the child likes already. For example, adding mashed vegetables (such as peas) to mashed potatoes.\n- When new food items are accepted by the child, use these items as “food bridges” to help you introduce other foods that are similar ���������������������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������������� mashed carrots.\n- Encourage children to feed themselves as much as possible using ������������������������������������������������������������������������ self-feeding skills and thus become more independent.\n- **Stick to** • A lot of children go through a picky eating phase which usually causes\n- **your plan** no harm. Try not to overthink it and do your best to help them grow out of it.\n- ��������������������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������������������� ���������������������������������������������������������������������",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_77_1_6": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### **Do NOT**\n- Do NOT count calories or weigh your child daily.\n- Do NOT label your child as “the picky eater.”\n- ����������������������������������������������������������������� won’t like anything.”\n- • Do NOT complain about your child’s eating behavior in front of them. • Do NOT inspect your child’s lunchbox or ask about their food intake the moment you see them.\n- •  Do NOT punish or scold your child for not eating.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n06<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_77_1_7": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### **Force-Feeding**\nMothers tend to get worried when their child eats very little, refuses to eat a meal or refuses to eat healthy foods like fruits and vegetables[[11]] �������������������������������������������������� especially if the child is underweight or not gaining weight adequately. For others, unconsumed meals can be a source of frustration, especially when the parents do not like to waste food that has been prepared, or when they believe that children have to ‘clean their plates’[[11]] .  As a result, parents may end up forcing their child to eat their entire meal.\nIt is true that the child may end up eating a bit more when being forced to eat. However, studies have shown that the act of forcing the child to eat can cause long-term problems for the child, which are summarized below:\n- **Disliking or avoiding certain foods.** This can be the result of a negative experience of ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� between foods and unpleasant experiences that may accompany them[ [11]] .\n- **Disturbing the child’s ability to respond to their internal feelings of hunger and fullness.** This means that the child would not listen to his/her body and so food intake becomes determined by other factors other than what the body requires. Instead, the child learns to continue eating, even when they feel full, stopping only when the plate is empty[ [11]] .\n- **Development of overeating and overweight.** As explained above, forcing the child to eat can disturb the child’s ability to learn appropriate appetite control. This can eventually lead to overeating and the development of overweight and obesity[ [11]] .\nExcept in rare cases, children are usually extremely good at knowing when they are full, and ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� that they will eat when feeling hungry. It is also important to remember that children have a natural tendency to reject new foods and this should not be met with pressure. Instead, continue ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� development. Also remember that the stomachs of young children are smaller than adults’ and you may be serving too much food that your child cannot consume.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n07<br>Vegetarian Children<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nSome families will choose to limit meat consumption or follow a vegetarian diet for health or �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� based foods (such as vegetables, fruits, cereals and starchy vegetables, legumes, unsalted, raw nuts and seeds), and usually excludes some or all foods from the animal-based food items such �������������������������������������������������������\nIf you choose this dietary pattern for your child, you should consult with a doctor or dietitian ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ suggests that, if done properly, and if monitored by a healthcare provider, vegetarian diets can meet the nutrient requirements of young children[[12-14]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_77_1_8": "### **CONTENTS**\n#### **08 Tips for A Healthy and Safe Lunchbox**\nSince foodborne illness are very common if foods are not properly stored in the lunchbox, or consumed at the right temperature, you need to follow some safety guidelines[[15]] :\n- For foods that should be kept cold, you might need to use an insulated bag with some sort �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� reusable cold source by simply adding a frozen water bottle or container to the lunchbox.\n- Avoid giving your child hot meals especially if the daycare/school does not have the option of heating foods. Remember that meals should be heated up to a safe temperature before being consumed.\nFor a healthy child’s lunchbox, follow the below guidelines (Box 3)[[16]] .\n|Box 3. Guidelines to follow when preparing your child’s lunchbox|Box 3. Guidelines to follow when preparing your child’s lunchbox|Box 3. Guidelines to follow when preparing your child’s lunchbox|\n|---|---|---|\n|**Choices**|•|Fill the lunchbox as such:|\n|||• ������������������������������������������������������|\n|||• ¼ of it with whole grain cereals|\n|||• ¼ of it with healthy proteins (legumes, turkey breast, unsalted, raw nuts/seeds)|\n||•|Add milk and/or dairy products to the main meal or snacks (such as a 200 mL pack|\n|||of pasteurized milk).|\n|**Preparation**|•|Make sure that the vegetables and fruits are thoroughly washed.|\n||•|Involve your child in the lunchbox preparation such as washing the vegetables and|\n|||��������������������������������������������������������������������|\n|||meal combination.|\n- **Presentation** • Cut the vegetables and fruits into small cubes or pieces, rather than putting them as whole food items.\n- • ����������������������������������������������������������\n- Green theme: Add lettuce, cucumbers as vegetables / apples, pears as fruits;\n- Red theme: Add cubes of a red tomato, slices of red pepper, raspberries, and strawberries.\n- • Incorporate more shapes: Present the sandwiches as small squares, or in the form of triangles; Use the dough-shaped cutters to cut the vegetables or fruits into nice shapes.\n- **Snack ideas** • Pair protein-rich foods with carbohydrate-rich foods: • 1 cup of plain yogurt with ½ a cup of strawberries or blueberries • 1 slice of whole wheat bread with peanut butter spread (1 tablespoon) • Carrot sticks with hummus dip • Cucumber cubes or slices with ½ a cup of labneh dip • 1 cup of seedless grapes with slices of white cheese\n- **Water** • Do not forget your child’s water bottle!\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n09<br>Food Safety Considerations<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nSafe preparation and handling of food are essential to reduce the susceptibility of toddlers and preschoolers to foodborne illnesses and food poisoning.\nRefer to Appendix 2 for general food safety guidelines.",
