  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_0": "## **10**\n### **Food Allergies**\n�����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������[[17]] . �����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������[ [17, ] 18]. The majority of children who have milk, egg, wheat or soy allergies would outgrow these ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� usually lifelong[ [17, 19]] .\nFood allergy is not the same as food intolerance, although the two terms are often mixed up. ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� immune system, whereas food allergies cause an immune system reaction[[17]] . The symptoms of food intolerance are usually less serious and are often limited to digestive problems. In contrast, ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� that can vary in their degree of severity. In some cases, allergic reactions may be very severe and life-threatening.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_1": "### **Food Allergies**\n#### **What are the most common allergens in the diet?**\n����������������������������������������������������������������������������[[17, 20]] :\n- Animal-based milk such as cow’s milk\n- Eggs\n- Peanuts\n- Soy\n- Tree nuts\n- Fish\n- �����������������������������������\n- Wheat\n- Seeds\n����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� type of food from your child’s diet[[20]] .\nSome individuals can have allergies for food additives including colors and preservatives, but usually allergic reactions from ordinary food items are more common[ [20]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_2": "### **Food Allergies**\n#### **What are the symptoms of food allergies?**\nAn allergic reaction can begin within minutes to an hour after ingesting the food or beverage that �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� more symptoms. The most common symptoms of food allergy are[[17]] :\n- Diarrhea\n- Vomiting\n- Cough\n- Swelling\n- Dry and itchy skin (eczema)\n- Itching or swelling of the lips, tongue, or mouth\n- Itching or tightness in the throat\n- Skin rashes\n- Sore, red and/or itchy eyes\n- Runny or blocked nose\n- Lowered blood pressure\n- Stomach cramps and pain\n- Red itchy bumps on the skin (hives)\n- Trouble breathing or shortness of breath\n- Wheezing (coarse sound when breathing)\nIn some cases, severe allergic reaction may occur which is known as “anaphylaxis”; this can be life-threating[[20,21]] ������������������������������������������������������������������������������ ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������[[17]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_3": "### **Food Allergies**\n#### **How do we diagnose a food allergy?**\n������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ unnecessary dietary restrictions. In case a food allergy is diagnosed, you must have a dietary plan to replace the eliminated food items, and you also need to have a plan in case of emergency[[19]] . If your child develops any of the typical allergy-related symptoms after eating any type of food or beverage, you should immediately contact a doctor.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_4": "### **Food Allergies**\n#### **Nutritional concerns in children with food allergies**\nIt is important to keep in mind that eliminating a certain food group (because of an allergy) ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� problems in your child[ [22]] . For example, milk, eggs and soy are good sources of fat and protein. ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� protein and fat in the diet if they are not replaced by other good sources[[22]] .\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� energy (calories) and certain vitamins, which can lead to poor growth.\n- Diets that are low in protein may also lead to protein malnutrition and hence poor growth [22].\nAnother example is wheat. This cereal provides the body with carbohydrates, which are known to be an important source of energy for your child’s body, and particularly the brain. Wheat also contains important vitamins and minerals. So if the child is allergic to wheat, other alternative �����������������������������������������������������������������������������[[22]] .\nAnother potential challenge is that children that have one or more food allergies might experience some dietary behavior problems more than other children. For example, they may develop “food aversion” (i.e. refusing certain types of food) or a state of anxiety about food, which again can lead to inadequate food intake[[22]] .\nThis is why it is very important that the doctor monitors the growth of children with food allergies [22]. It is also important that the doctor or dietitians provide you with the right alternatives to ����������������������������������������������������������������������[ [22]] .  Supplements may sometimes be prescribed by the doctor when needed[[22]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_5": "### **Food Allergies**\n#### **What should I do if my child was diagnosed with a food allergy?**\n������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ food or beverage that causes the allergic reaction[[17, 19, 21, 23]] . It is therefore important to get the help of a dietitian to plan an adequate, healthy and balanced diet for your child, to avoid any �������������������������������������������������������������������������������[[23]] . Below are some practical tips that can help you in managing your child’s food allergy:\n- Check with a dietitian and a doctor to identify food alternatives or even nutritional �������������������������������������[[17]] .\n- ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������[[19]] .\n- Educate your family (at home) and teachers (in the school or nursery) about your child’s allergies and what to do in case of an emergency[[19]] .\n- If the doctor has prescribed any medications in case of an allergic reaction, always keep those medications at hand[[17]] .\n- ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������� complications caused by food allergies[ [21]] .\n���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� allergies, after a certain amount of time to evaluate whether the child has outgrown the allergy. Some allergies may in fact be outgrown with time and the foods may end up being tolerated after reaching the age of three or four years old. This must be done under the doctor’s supervision[[17]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_6": "### **Food Allergies**\n#### **Tips when dining out of the house:**\nAs a parent of a child with one or more food allergies, it can be challenging to eat out of the house. The following tips can help you:\n- Check the menu online before going to the restaurant.\n- Read and/or ask about the ingredients before ordering any dish.\n- Let the server be aware of your child’s allergy and ensure there is no cross-contamination when preparing your child’s dish.\n- ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� �������������������������������������������������\n- ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� dishes[[17]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_7": "### **Food Allergies**\n#### **Food allergy card:**\nHaving a food allergy card can help your child and especially help the people around them (if you ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� with the child at all times, including at the school or nursery, or when the child is visiting a friend, at a party and/or in a restaurant. Inform any adult in charge that the child has this card, such as the teacher at the school or nursery the parents of the friend that your child is visiting[ [17]] .\nThe food allergy card should contain the following information:\n- The name of the child\n- Food items your child is allergic to\n- What to do in case of emergency\n- Parent’s name and phone number\nThis card can be easily done at home (below is the card template).\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nFOOD ALLERGY CARD<br>My name is  .....................................................................................................................................................................<br>I am allergic to  ..........................................................................................................................................................<br>.....................................................................................................................................................................................................<br>.....................................................................................................................................................................................................<br>I cannot eat food containing .......................................................................................................................<br>.....................................................................................................................................................................................................<br>.....................................................................................................................................................................................................<br>even in small amounts, so please avoid any form of cross-contamination.<br>In case of emergency, please call 999 and notify my parents.<br>My parents contact number: ...................................................<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n11 Oral Health<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nProper oral health among children paves the way for good health and wellbeing as they grow older. Early childhood is the most convenient time for your child to acquire healthy habits since at this age, they would have started to drink and eat on their own. Unhealthy diets and improper oral health habits may increase your child’s risk of dental decays, especially if your child engages in the following behaviors[[24]] :\n- Regular and frequent consumption of sugary foods like cakes, biscuits,  candies, and chocolates\n- Regular and frequent consumption of sugar-sweetened beverages like fruit juices and carbonated soft drinks (i.e., carbonated beverages)\n- Not cleaning or brushing their teeth\nHence, it is extremely important that you consider the below recommendations to ensure adequate oral health for your child (Box 4)[ [24]] .\nBox 4. Recommendations to ensure adequate oral health for your child\n- �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� such as vegetables, fruits, and yogurt.\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ �������������������\n- Watch your child brush their teeth and help them until they have acquired good brushing techniques.\n- Try to make teeth brushing fun by using a timer (2 minutes). Let them use a toothbrush with an animated character that they like; this will motivate them to brush their teeth.\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� recommendation.\n- Ensure your child is having regular dental check-ups with a dentist (at least every 6 months).\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n12<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_8": "### **Food Allergies**\n#### **Your Child’s Food Choices**\nEvery parent tries their best to ensure that their child eats healthy most of the time, but there [25].\nFood and beverage options that are advertised in the media (TV or social media) are not always nutritious or healthy for your child. In fact, most of the advertised food and beverages are high [26]. Children have a remarkable ability to remember content from these advertisements and thus they tend to develop a preference for the marketed foods[[25, 27-29]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_9": "### **Food Allergies**\n#### **choices?[[26]]**\n- Avoid the use of TVs and tablets or any other electronic device while eating:\n- Apply this to the whole family during main meals as well as snacks.\n- Eat together as a family without any distractions to promote healthy eating as well as family bonding.\n- Choose children’s programs without advertisements:\n- Choose platforms that allow you to skip commercials, or that do not include any.\n- Involve your child when buying and preparing foods:\n- Children are willing to learn about everything at this age, and they enjoy being involved in doing small tasks around the house; this is a good opportunity to teach them about healthy food and beverages and let them be part of choosing, buying, and preparing meals and snacks.\n- Limit screen time:\n- Limit screen time to a maximum of one hour per day.\n- Be a role model to your child:\n- Young children will imitate their parents and view them as their role models. Be mindful of your choices. Choose healthy foods and beverages and limit your screen time to encourage your child to do the same.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_10": "### **Food Allergies**\n#### **13 Physical Activity Recommendations For Toddlers and Preschoolers**\nEncourage your child to lead a healthy and active lifestyle by being involved in unstructured or structured play for a minimum of 3 hours a day[[30]] .\n��������������������������������������������������������������������������[ [30]] :\n- It promotes healthy and strong bones and muscles, while improving movement skills\n- It helps maintain a healthy body weight\n- It improves social and intellectual skills\nBox 5 below provides you with the physical activity recommendations for toddlers and preschoolers [30].",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_11": "### **Food Allergies**\n#### Box 5. Physical activity guidelines for toddlers and preschoolers\n- Encourage your child to enjoy a variety of activities throughout the day, such as riding the bicycle, running, jumping, and swimming.\n- Make sure to use protective gear such as bicycle helmets, knee pads and chin guards, to help reduce the risk of injuries.\n- Gradually increase the frequency, time, and intensity of exercising as your child is growing and developing.\n- Limit long hours of inactivity by encouraging your child to move more and by making physical activity part of their daily routine. Encourage a break from sitting, every 20-30 minutes.\n- Limit screen time (television, computer, phones, tablets) to less than an hour per day.\nEvery child is ������������������������� activities should be based on their current physical maturity. Gradually increase frequency, intensity, and time of new physical activities to reduce **REMEMBER** the risk of injury. Accidents happen more frequently when your child gets tired or due to missing protective gear.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n14 Importance of Adequate Sleep<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nAdequate sleep plays a major role in modulating the health and wellbeing of your child. ������������������������������������������������������������������������������[[31, 32]] , and can increase the risk of developing chronic diseases, such as hypertension, cardiovascular diseases and type II diabetes later in life[[32, 33]] . In addition, lack of sleep can have a negative impact on the following[ [33, 34]] :\n- Physical and mental health\n- Cognitive and psychosocial development\n- Alertness and attention\n- Vocabulary acquisition (process of learning new words)\n- Learning and memory\n- Mood\nBox 6 provides you with the recommendations for sleep among toddlers and preschoolers[ [32, 33, 35]] .",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_78_1_12": "### **Food Allergies**\n#### Box 6. Recommendations for sleep among toddlers and preschoolers\n- Make sure that your child is getting good quality of sleep as follows:\n- 11-14 hours of sleep, including naps, for children aged 2-3 years old.\n- 10-13 hours of sleep, including naps, for children aged 3-5 years old. Naps at this age become shorter; preschoolers might even stop napping.\n- Establish a consistent bedtime routine. Reading a book, or having a hot warm bath can help.\n- �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� bedtime. Let the bed be a no-screen zone.\n- Make sure that the bedroom is quiet, calm and at a room temperature convenient for your child.\n- Having your child put on their favorite pajamas is a good strategy to encourage them to go to bed.\n- ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������\n- Encourage your child to have a proper physical activity routine, which can help them sleep better at night. Refer to section 13.\n- Do not forget proper teeth brushing before bedtime! (Refer to Section 11).",
