  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_79_1_1": "### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n#### **Examples of one portion of vegetable:**\n- 2-6 carrot sticks\n- 1-3 cherry tomatoes\n- ½-2 tablespoons of roasted vegetables\n- ½-1 small bowl of homemade vegetable soup",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_79_1_2": "### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n#### **Examples of one portion of fruit:**\n- ¼-½ medium apple, orange, pear, mango, or peach\n- ¼-1 medium banana\n- ½-1 clementine, apricot, plum\n- 3-10 strawberries, raspberries, blueberries, grapes\n- 1-3 dates\n-",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_79_1_3": "### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n#### **CEREALS AND STARCHY VEGETABLES**\n�������������������������������������������������������������������������������� General recommendations are 5 portions per day\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\n1 Portion<br>2-5 tablespoons ½-1 bread slice 3-6 tablespoons ¼-½ baked potato<br>cooked rice breakfast cereals<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_79_1_4": "### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n#### **Examples of one portion:**\n- 2-5 tablespoons of cooked rice or pasta\n- 2-4 tablespoons of couscous\n- ½-1 bread slice, chapatti bread\n- ¼-½ pita bread\n- 3-6 tablespoons of breakfast cereals\n- ¼-½ baked potato, medium-sized; ½-1 ½ egg-sized boiled potatoes",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_79_1_5": "### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n#### **Practical tips:**\n- Add cereals and starchy vegetables to each meal.\n- ������������������������������������������������\n- Keep biscuits, cakes, pastries, and pies for special occasions.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_79_1_6": "### **VEGETABLES AND FRUITS**\n#### **LEGUMES**\nEat legumes daily. Legumes are counted as a protein rich food.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nLENTILS BEANS CHICKPEAS  RAW NUTS<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nMaintain a daily consumption of protein foods, including legumes, unsalted, raw nuts and �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� details on the number of portions and portion sizes.\n- �������������������\n- Include foods rich in vitamin C to enhance absorption of iron and zinc from legumes.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_80_0_0": "## **MILK, DAIRY PRODUCTS AND ALTERNATIVES**\nMaintain a daily consumption of milk and dairy products General recommendations are 3 portions per day\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nMILK, DAIRY PRODUCTS AND ALTERNATIVES<br>1 Portion<br>100-120 mL 3 tablespoons 2-4 tablespoons 2-4 tablespoons<br>milk plain yogurt  grated cheese rice pudding<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_80_1_0": "## **MILK, DAIRY PRODUCTS AND ALTERNATIVES**\n### **Examples of one portion:**\n- 100-120 mL of milk\n- 3 tablespoons of plain yogurt or 125 mL of laban\n- 1 cheese ball or 2-4 tablespoons of grated cheese\n- 2-4 tablespoons of rice pudding",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_80_1_1": "### **Examples of one portion:**\n#### **FISH, POULTRY, MEAT AND ALTERNATIVES**\nThese foods are rich sources of protein.\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nFISH POULTRY AND MEAT EGGS NUTS AND SEEDS<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\nMaintain a daily consumption of protein foods, including legumes, nuts and seeds and/or ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� number of portions and portion sizes.\n- Fish, poultry, meat, eggs, unsalted, raw nuts and seeds, and legumes are good sources of protein.\n- �������������������������������������������\n- ��������������������������������������������������������\n**----- Start of picture text -----**<br>\nBox 1:  Protein Foods<br>**----- End of picture text -----**<br>\n**Make sure to include protein rich foods in your child’s daily diet. These include legumes, �������������������������������������������������������������������**\nGeneral recommendations for protein foods are 2 portions per day.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_80_1_2": "### **Examples of one portion:**\n#### **Examples of one portion include:**\n- 2-4 tablespoons of cooked beans, chickpeas or lentils\n- 15-30 g of seafood, skinless chicken, and lean meats\n- ½-1 ½  tablespoon of canned sardines\n- ½-1 ½ tablespoon of canned tuna (in water not oil)\n- ½-1 boiled egg\n- 1-2 tablespoons of chopped or ground unsalted, raw nuts or seeds\n- 1-2 tablespoons of hummus\n- 1 tablespoon of peanut butter\nThe number of portions of protein per day increases with the child’s age: 2 portions/day for toddlers aged 1-2 years; 2-5 portions for children aged 2-5 years.",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_80_1_3": "### **Examples of one portion:**\n#### **APPENDIX 2:**\n����������������������������������\nEating food that is contaminated with certain bacteria, viruses, parasites or contains harmful toxins can cause foodborne illnesses. These illnesses are usually acute, occurring within 1 to 36 hours after the consumption of the contaminated or poisonous food. The symptoms normally last from 1 to 7 days and include one or more of the following symptoms: abdominal pain, diarrhea, vomiting, feeling sick, dehydration and collapsing. Foods that are most likely to contain harmful bacteria or viruses fall into two categories:\n1. Uncooked fresh vegetables and fruits\n2. Some animal products, such as unpasteurized (raw) milk; soft cheeses made with raw milk; ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� juices; luncheon meats and deli-type salads (without added preservatives)\nWhile the majority of children who develop a foodborne illness will get better without medical interventions, if symptoms are severe or persist for more than a week, it is advisable to consult with a doctor.\nPreparing and consuming safe foods starts at the time of food purchase. Box 1 outlines a few tips to assist you in shopping for safe food for your children.\nBox 1. Tips for safe food purchase\n- Purchase food from reliable sources.\n- Read the “Product Label” for food safety information on all foods and beverages.\n- Put raw seafood, poultry, or meat in separate plastic bags.\n- Pick up perishable foods last, and plan to go directly home from the grocery store.\n- Buy only pasteurized milk, soft cheeses made with pasteurized milk, and pasteurized juices that have been treated to control harmful bacteria.\n- Always purchase refrigerated eggs.\n- Do not buy food displayed in unsafe or unclean conditions.\n- Always check the expiry date of the food to be purchased:\n- A “Sell-By” or “Expiry (EXP)” date tells the store how long to display the product for ���������������������������������������������������������\n- �� �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� not a purchase or safety date.\n- A “Use-By” date is the last date recommended for the use of the product while at peak quality. The date has been determined by the manufacturer of the product.\n������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� handling and consumption. These practices fall under the following four categories: **Clean, Separate, Cook and Chill** . More details about these practices are outlined in Box 2[[37]] .\n|Box 2. Tips for proper food handling|Box 2. Tips for proper food handling|\n|---|---|\n|**Clean:**|• Wash your hands, before, during and after food preparation and|\n||consumption.|\n||• Wash your hands for at least 60 seconds.|\n||• Practice good personal hygiene during food handling and preparation|\n||activities.|\n||• Clean your kitchen! Keep all food preparation premises clean; wash|\n||counters, tabletops, cooking surfaces and the sink with hot, soapy water|\n||before you cook and after they come into contact with raw seafood,|\n||������������������������|\n||• Clean your food! Wash vegetables and fruits with clean water, before|\n||peeling. Vinegar may also be used to disinfect vegetables and fruits.|\n||• Limit washing eggs, raw meat and poultry since washing causes bacteria|\n||to spread faster. Instead, pat the eggs with a clean, damp towel, and the|\n||raw meat and poultry with a separate damp towel as well.|\n||• Wipe food packaging with soap and water before opening, especially lids|\n||of cans and jars.|\n|**Separate:**|• Keep cooked and ready-to-eat foods away from raw seafood, poultry,|\n||meat, and eggs in the refrigerator and while cooking. (Juices from raw|\n||seafood, poultry, meats and cracked eggs can contaminate ready-to-eat|\n||foods, so it is important to separate them.)|\n||• Ensure that cooked and ready-to-eat foods are placed on top shelves,|\n||while raw foods are placed on lower shelves in the refrigerator, in order to|\n||prevent the transfer of bacteria from the raw foods to the cooked foods.|\n||• If possible, use separate sets of knives, cutting boards, and utensils for|\n||seafood, poultry, meat, and eggs. Ensure to wash them in hot, soapy|\n||water or in the dishwasher between uses.|\n||• Plates that touch raw foods are not safe to reuse for cooked foods until|\n||they have been washed. Use clean plates to hold cooked foods, and wash|\n||plates thoroughly in hot, soapy water after they touch raw foods.|\n- **Cook:** • Use clean water. • Cook all food thoroughly:\n- The cooking temperature needs to reach at least 75º C or above to ensure the food is safe and free from all pathogenic bacteria.\n- A food thermometer must be used to measure the internal temperature of cooked foods. Check the internal temperature in several places to make sure that the seafood, poultry, meat, or egg product is cooked to safe minimum internal temperatures.\n- For microwave or oven cooking: always cover food, stir, and rotate for even cooking.\n- Consume leftovers within 3-4 days.\n- Reheat leftovers only once. If leftovers are not consumed after being reheated, throw them out.\n- **Chill:** • ���������������������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������������������ harmful bacteria.\n- • Do not keep food at room temperature for more than 2 hours.\nThere are a few general guidelines that will help reduce the risk of foodborne illnesses:\n- Protect food from insects, rodents, and other animals.\n- Store non-perishable food products in a cool and dry place.\n- ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� fruit juice.\n- �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������\n- ��������������������������������������������������������������",
  "SRC013_CHUNK_0_80_1_4": "### **Examples of one portion:**\n#### **REFERENCES**\n1. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Childhood overweight and obesity: consequences of obesity. Available online: https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/childhood/ consequences.html (accessed on 4 April 2022).\n2. World Health Organization. Nutrition Landscape Information System (NLiS). Malnutrition in children. Available online: https://www.who.int/data/nutrition/nlis/info/malnutrition-inchildren (accessed on 4 April 2022).\n3. United States Department of Agriculture. Healthy eating for preschoolers. Available online: https://www.myplate.gov/tip-sheet/healthy-eating-preschoolers (accessed on 31 March 2022).\n4. United States Department of Agriculture. MyPlate [website]. Available online: https:// www.myplate.gov/ (accessed on 4 April 2022).\n5. ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������\n6. Instritute of Medicine. Dietary Reference Intakes for Water, Potassium, Sodium, Chloride, and Sulfate; The National Academies Press: Washington, DC, 2005; Available online: https://www.nap.edu/catalog/10925/dietary-reference-intakes-for-water-potassiumsodium-chloride-and-sulfate.\n7. Pai, U. A.; Chandrasekhar, P.; Carvalho, R. S.; Kumar, S. The role of nutrition in immunity in infants and toddlers: An expert panel opinion. Clin Epidemiol Glob Health 2018, 6, 155-159.\n8. Connor, Z. Help for children who are extremely fussy eaters; National Health Service: UK, 2019; Available online: https://publicdocuments.sth.nhs.uk/pil4379.pdf.\n9. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Picky Eaters and What to Do. Available online: https://www.cdc.gov/nutrition/infantandtoddlernutrition/foods-and-drinks/pickyeaters.html (accessed on 31 March 2022).\n10. American Academy of Pediatrics. 10 tips for parents of picky eaters. Available online: https://www.healthychildren.org/English/ages-stages/toddler/nutrition/Pages/PickyEaters.aspx (accessed on 31 March 2022).\n11. Child feeding guide. Common feeding pitfalls: pressure to eat. Available online: https:// www.childfeedingguide.co.uk/tips/common-feeding-pitfalls/pressure-eat/ (accessed on 1 December 2022).\n12. Kleinman, R.; Greer, F. Pediatric Nutrition, 8th ed; American Academy of Pediatrics: 2019; pp.\n13. American Academy of Pediatrics. Where We Stand: Soy Formulas. Available online: https://www.healthychildren.org./English/ages-stages/baby/feeding-nutrition/Pages/ Where-We-Stand-Soy-Formulas.aspx (accessed on 31 March 2022).\n14. Craig, W.; Mangels, A. Position of the American Dietetic Association: Vegetarian Diets. J Am Diet Assoc 2009, 109, 1266-1282.\n15. United States Department of Agriculture. Use an insulated lunch bag to keep meals safe. Available online: https://www.usda.gov/media/blog/2019/08/13/use-insulated-lunch-bagkeep-meals-safe (accessed on 31 March 2022).\n16. Harvard - School of Public Health. Packing a healthy lunchbox. Available online: https:// www.hsph.harvard.edu/nutritionsource/kids-healthy-lunchbox-guide/ (accessed on 31 March 2022).\n17. Johns Hopkins Medicine. Food allergies in children. Available online: https://www. hopkinsmedicine.org/health/conditions-and-diseases/food-allergies-in-children (accessed on 7 March 2022).\n18. Zeiger, R. S. Food allergen avoidance in the prevention of food allergy in infants and children. Pediatrics 2003, 111, 1662-1671.\n19. Hayes, D.; de Jesús, D. Reducing the Risk of Food Allergies - Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics. Available online: https://www.eatright.org/health/allergies-and-intolerances/ food-allergies/reducing-the-risk-of-food-allergies (accessed on 23 March 2022).\n20. National Health Service. Food allergies in babies and young children. Available online: https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/baby/weaning-and-feeding/food-allergies-in-babies-andyoung-children/ (accessed on 7 March 2022).\n21. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. CDC healthy school: food allergies. Available online: https://www.cdc.gov/healthyschools/foodallergies/index.htm (accessed on 22 March 2022).\n22. Mehta, H.; Groetch, M.; Wang, J. Growth and nutritional concerns in children with food allergy. Curr Opin Allergy Clin Immunol 2013, 13, 275-279.\n23. Mazzocchi, A.; Venter, C.; Maslin, K.; Agostoni, C. The role of nutritional aspects in food allergy: prevention and management. Nutrients 2017, 9, 850.\n24. Government of New South Wales - Australia. Healthy mouths healthy living: advice for children 0-5 years. Available online: https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/oralhealth/prevention/ �������������������������������������������������������������������� �������������������������������������������������������������������������\n25. �������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ child-eats/amp/ (accessed on 31 March 2022).\n26. ���������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� your-child-eats (accessed on 31 March 2022).\n27. ����������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� branding on young children’s taste preferences. Arch Pediatr Adolesc Med 2007, 161, 792797.\n28. ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� health cues on children’s ratings of cereal taste. Arch Pediatr Adolesc Med 2011, 165, 229234.\n29. ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������� of television (TV) food advertisements/commercials on caloric intake and food choice of 5–7-year-old children. Appetite 2007, 49, 263-267.\n30. Aspetar. Qatar National Physical Activity Guidelines, 2nd edition; Aspetar Orthopaedic and Sports Medicine Hospital: Doha, Qatar, 2021; Available online:\n31. ������������������������������������������������������������������������������������������ systematic review and meta-analysis. Obesity 2008, 16, 265.\n32. World Health Organization. Guidelines on physical activity, sedentary behaviour and sleep for children under 5 years of age; World Health Organization: Geneva, Switzerland, 2019; Available online: https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/hand le/10665/311664/9789241550536-eng.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y.\n33. Sleep Foundation. Children and sleep. Available online: https://www.sleepfoundation.org/ children-and-sleep (accessed on 1 April 2022).\n34. Chaput, J.-P.; Gray, C. E.; Poitras, V. J.; Carson, V.; Gruber, R.; Olds, T.; Weiss, S. K.; Connor Gorber, S.; Kho, M. E.; Sampson, M. Systematic review of the relationships between sleep duration and health indicators in school-aged children and youth. Appl Physiol Nutr Metab 2016, 41, S266-S282.\n35. Sleep Foundation. How much sleep do babies and kids need? Available online: https://www. ��������������������������������������������������������������������������������� ���������������������������������������������������������������������������� April 2022).\n36. British Nutrition Foundation. Perfect portions for little tums (1-4 years); 2019; Available online: https://www.therockinghorse-nursery.com/attachments/download. ��������������������\n37. World Health Organization. Five keys to safer food manual; World Health Organization: Geneva, Switzerland, 2006; Available online: https://www.who.int/foodsafety/ publications/consumer/manual_keys.pdf?ua=1.\n43\n44\nCHAPTER 7\nCHOOSE HEALTHY FATS AND REDUCE SUGAR AND SALT IN YOUR CHILD’S DIET\n1\n2",
